Date: Tue, 17 Aug 2004 11:07:51 +0100
Subject: Re: [livecode] ultrasound blurb
From: Alex <mail


Hey alex,

I may have a suggestion to give as an external listener to your interesting
discussion.

It may actually be good to state shortly and firstly what are the different
possibilities a musician has to compose/play music with a computer. Many
people are still very confused about it (even musicians themselves). At
least the difference between "live composition" and the use of tools to play
existing (prerecorded ?) material. People may have already a little idea
about it (or not at all) but they would more easily understand your point
after that.

> Some computer languages allow changing a running process on the fly by
> rewriting the code that defines it. Applied to computer music this means
> that one can write sound compositions while they are already playing.

The relationship between computer languages and "computer music" is for you
natural and when your are talking about it, I hear a guitarist or a piano
player talking about its instrument. But the link is far from being obvious
to people generally and moreover for traditional musicians who are still
very much going towards computers for their abilities to sequence and edit
music and not so much for composing.

For this you may have to go through a rough explanation of the entity of
electronic music or how a computer "understand" music. A good introduction
to this has been written by Miller Puckette, as an online book:
http://crca.ucsd.edu/~msp/techniques.htm

Sure, for a short proposal, it may difficult to condense this in one or two
phrases but I think they are quite essential.

WOOOW this is very interesting guys, I keep on listening....
Alex (the French one).





From: "N. Collins" <nc272
Subject: Re: [livecode] ultrasound blurb
Date: 17 Aug 2004 13:01:11 +0100


I've added/amended below- one important one, changed Algorithmic 
Programming to Algorithm Programming- the human action is in writing 
algorithms on the fly. You could metarise this to Algorithmic production of 
programs, but Algorithm covers the meta-levels too whereas Algorithmic 
Programming is either a tautology or a specialism.
 
Some of this can be adapted expanded (and chuck in a few things from our 
papers...) for other proposals. N
 

Some computer languages allow a programmer to change a running process on 
the fly by rewriting the code that defines it. If the output of that code 
is a process being revealed to human senses, an interactive performance is 
possible. Applied to live computer music this means sound compositions can 
be heard as they form, and musical algorithms adjusted while already 
playing.
 
TOPLAP is the Temporary Organisation for the Promotion of Live Algorithm 
Programming, set up to explore the application of live programming to 
composition and performance. TOPLAP advocates treating algorithms as live 
artistic material, allowing them to be written and manipulated while they 
create music or video, perhaps in front of an audience.

The interests of the TOPLAP membership encompass live coding performances 
with output in both audio and visual modalities, the possibilities of 
immediate feedback given by prototyping compositions in interpreted 
programming languages and new languages for on-the-fly programming. This 
international organisation is gathering membership and profile. Recent 
performances and demonstrations have taken place in Japan, USA, Sweden, 
Germany, England and Denmark.

TOPLAP proposes an evening of performances from live coders, with both 
audio and visual outputs. The audience will see and hear the created 
musical and visual material, and also the projected screens of the 
participants so that the processes are entirely open and the craft 
apparent. The coded improvisations show a novel blend of intellectual and 
emotional content that challenges existing notions of both traditional 
haptic instrumental and DJ like laptop performance.

(this is where I'd list who'd play, but we''d need confirmations and prob. 
unecessary at this point- Alex, Nick, Dave using fluxus? dream list- 
Julian/Alberto, Ge...)

Further information on TOPLAP artists, events and theory is available at:
http://www.toplap.org



From: "Dave Griffiths" <dave
Subject: [livecode] a notation system for live coding music
Date: Tue, 17 Aug 2004 14:47:51 +0100


Hi all,

I've been doing more work on the live music tools I used for placard, and I
thought I'd document the score system a bit more formally, as It's become
integral to the whole setup, and might be of interest to other people:

http://www.pawfal.org/index.php?page=ScoreCode

I've mentioned it here before, I'm still not sure if it counts as live coding,
but the way it's used is to have text entry fields for the axiom and rules of
an l system which produces the final (usually quite large) score strings that
the sequencer can play.

There is a screenshot of the old setup here:
http://www.pawfal.org/Software/noiseengine/images/live.png
The five windows along the middle of the screen are the melodic lsystem
generators, with the axiom entry at the top - all containing "!1" which simply
resets the frequency and instanciates rule 1. The four text entry fields in
the middle are the rules.

Looking forward to seeing some of you in Arhus, looks like it could be quite
popular, I'm having quite a bit of difficulty finding somewhere to stay - so
it could be the campsite for me :)

cheers,

dave



