Date: Thu, 09 Dec 2004 09:44:33 +0000
From: Nick Collins <nc272
Subject: Re: [livecode] [Fwd: Re: toplap workshop at transmediale]



> So it looks like Nick's ideas of concentrated workshops are more
> sensible, apologies Nick, we should have gone for that in the first
> place.
>

Yeah, your proposal was a bit passive for a workshop audience- they don't 
attend to watch, it's surely more fun to get them trying stuff out 
themselves.

I like the idea of a ChucK and jitlib workshop, half day each, participants 
get explanations and to explore both. I know I'd be very happy to attend 
such a workshop. Again, Ge and Julian/Alberto, thoughts?

In terms of covering many systems, I think that's too ambitious, and some 
systems are more naturally set up for people other than the original 
creator. It's hard work to teach/install custom stuff which has probably 
only ever had one user. ChucK and jitlib have the advantage of being 
available in advance, cross platform without overly specific installation 
requirements, and have many natural help resources. They are designed for 
third party end-users.

> However, a good thing has come from our bold proposal, Carsten is
> looking to see if we can do two hours worth of presentations in the main
> conference space.  His mail is attached.  Thoughts appreciated as ever!

It is good consequence that you may have pumped up the presentation time, 
so there is no fear of missing out anyone who wanted to present something.

cheers for your constant energy and enthusiasm Alex
N


