From: Adrian Ward <adrian
Subject: [livecode] Fodder for Ars Electronica
Date: Tue, 22 Feb 2005 16:51:58 +0000



Hello TOPLAPpers,

I'm collecting small bits of footage for the Ars Electronica DVD 
submission (or more generally for a mini documentary) that I'll edit. 
I've got a lot of video footage from Fredrik (thanks!) of our 
Transmediale event, but I'd like to get some audio snippets of as many 
of you as possible talking, a bit like a one-on-one interview, although 
obviously conducted remotely, via the Internet, in non-realtime. You 
could imagine me sitting in-front of you asking these questions if you 
think it helps, although I can't imagine that'd be the case. Don't let 
it disturb you too much.

So just set your microphones recording (doesn't need to be very high 
quality, but at least 16 bit @ 22kHz please) and answer these 
questions:

0. Please tell me your personal interpretation of the T.O.P.L.A.P. 
acronym.
1. Who are you, and what the hell do you think you're doing?
2. So why don't you just go and play a regular musical instrument?
3. So you're saying that musicians are going to be replaced by robots 
eh? (imagine I'm the narrow minded tabloid journalist for this one)
4. Why is live coding compelling?
5. What is the next live coding thing you're going to do?

I'm only looking for a few minutes of dialogue maximum. Once done, 
compress as an MP3/OGG/etc and upload it via 
http://www.signwave.co.uk/go/clients/upload - or onto your own servers 
and mail me a link.

I'm hoping to start building the video this week and the deadline for 
Ars Electronica is getting close.

Mail me if there's any questions. The more input the better!

Cheers,


-- 
Adrian Ward, Signwave UK
http://www.signwave.co.uk/ - +44(0)7711 623498
2nd Floor North, Rutland House, 42-46 New Road, London, E1 2AX, UK.



From: Fredrik Olofsson <f
Subject: Re: [livecode] re: happy codeday
Date: Sat, 26 Feb 2005 18:50:47 +0100


hi list,
thought i'd mention that i got some tough critique after the jam at 
maria.  my friends were provoked (but not enough to stand up and 
leave...)  main objection was that there were too few outstanding 
ideas.  it all blurred sonically and visually.
my comment is that as 10 people improvising with laptops is bound to 
fail live coding or not, i think we sort of made it through all right.  
and it was great fun to get together with you all.

but i still think we should've ended it nice and clean while at our 
peak (alp top) by collectively, live onstage, wiping our harddrives 
holding hands singing 'we shall overcome'.  after transmediale, and 
specially the c-base gig, i've second thoughts about coding live on 
stage.  it's just a too good excuse for me to not prepare anything.

_f


   #|
      fredrikolofsson.com     klippav.org     musicalfieldsforever.com
   |#



