Date: Thu, 19 May 2005 09:21:11 +0100
From: Nick Collins <nc272
Subject: Re: [livecode] ICMC Inspirational Ideas


Do people have any exciting and entirely unimplemented ideas about the=20
future of live coding? I enclose a few below off the top of my head, I'm=20
sure others have better thought out proposals. I have dropped worries about =

spotting the halting problem etc in the below- besides which, I think=20
humans often miss potential infinite loops...also, I'm sure some research=20
in computer science is directed especially at the first of these:

programming style analysis- artificial agents look at a corpus of your=20
coding style and try to predict the things you will do, as subversion or=20
support. It's like a monster auto-complete given free reign over your=20
present self. David Cope style statistical analysis might be a way in here, =

EACI- experiments in artistic coding intelligence.

coding a large scale project collaboratively as performance. In this piece, =

each coder is assigned part of a larger specification than they could=20
complete alone. (a composer provides the spec). The project is designed so=20
that temporary stubs can be gradually expanded into the finished product,=20
giving snapshots of the generative beast along the way.

Deconstructing Codey. In this game (eventually for future child musicians)=20
a well known music algorithm is taken to pieces. Each player gets to remove =

a line at a time. The game is over when the algorithm stops outputting=20
anything. So it's a live coding Jenga.

Auto GUI- running code is given GUI controls automatically so that others=20
can manipulate it. This requires some building in of explicit input specs=20
for algorithms, but might give some promising directions. Perhaps scuppered =

by changing functionality during live coding, and removes flexibility? I=20
have seen limited forms of this, ie in Crucial system for SC.

Any advances?
N


