Subject: Re: [livecode] some writing
From: alex <alex
Date: Thu, 06 Oct 2005 22:50:04 +0100


On Thu, 2005-10-06 at 14:33 -0700, paul webb wrote:
> but has the free software movement buggered things up
> for artists who used be able to make some small income
> doing shareware stuff...

I'm not sure what the connection between artists and shareware is here.
Maybe you're suggesting that artists don't like doing proper marketing,
and prefer shareware's viral marketing?  Or is there some shareware art
culture I haven't heard about?

> its made the issue so black and white....
> either big money corps... or free software open source

I think the real opportunity for individuals to make money from software
is with on-line apps, but again I don't know what this has to do with
artists.

alex




From: Paul Sanders <paul
Subject: Re: [livecode] some writing
Date: Thu, 6 Oct 2005 23:09:05 +0100



i think some people in the free and open source world should expose  
themselves to commercial software a bit more. it's playing to the  
gallery to suggest that commercial programmers are perverted  
flatterers, and that the software tricks its users into being less  
creative. and really - open source people don't flatter each other?  
what nonsense.

i'm using bidule - which has a similar paradigm to pure data. it's  
commercial, which wasn't a factor in my choice (except that spending  
money is painful, so i would rather not). i don't recognise terms  
like 'high level' and 'low level' applied to music creation tools -  
tools work with us to give expression to our musical impulses. there  
is only one level, and that's the level that the artist is working at.

i'm not very good yet. i must practise. but what a miserablist  
position to take that i have to make my own sine waves before i can  
be considered a 'real' artist - and that if the bidule guys have made  
some for me then that's them generating my art, not me! selmer made  
my saxophone, and i loved it for what it let me do to the air around  
me, and i loved them for making it. did selmer make my music? no. i  
fucking did.

there. i vented. alex - you know i love what you do and hugely admire  
how you do it.

paul
de-lurking - and i have been lurking around this field of endeavour  
for about 15 years!



Date: Thu, 6 Oct 2005 15:29:06 -0700 (PDT)
From: paul webb <paulwebb
Subject: Re: [livecode] some writing



Hi Alex.

what this has to do with artists is that artist do
need to make some kind of income, and I think it is
preferably that this money is earned from doing their
work, rather than have to go out and do work they
perhaps don't want to do.  So make money from doing
festivals, exhibitions, selling their work, doing
talks. Or writing software and trying to sell it. Like
how "fine artists" sell their work.
I would rather it was the case that artists could do
their stuff and not have to worry about income. But
this is not the case... and is likely to get worse.


I have found over the last 10 years that people expect
more and more that experimental software (whether it
is classed as artistic or not) should be free. Maybe
this is my experience. And others in the free software
movement I have spoken to about have agreed that free
software has meant people think s/w should be free.
But they don't see it as a problem. Maybe it isn't.

I don't know if there is a shareware s/w art culture.
But maybe this is just part of s/w art culture in
which the artists  sell their work. Which I think is
small.=20

am I making any sense.,,
probably not

paul






























