Date: Sun, 16 Apr 2006 21:08:58 +0200
From: Sylvain <sylbx.le-beux
Subject: Re: [livecode] new members


Hi Everyone,

I am a new member too, so I guess I should introduce myself. Concerning=20
my relationship with music and more particulary electronic music : I=20
played the piano for almost ten years in my early age, and am trying to=20
practice back now after a long stop. I began playing electronic about 5=20
years ago, after buying an hardware sampler, I then began being=20
attracted by software, that I intensitvely try to have a whole look at.=20
I thus in chronologial order tried Cubase, Frooty loops, Reason,=20
Max/MSP, Pure Data, Supercollider, Chuck ... naming only the main ones.=20
After having a laptop stolen about 6 months ago with about 2 years work=20
on it, I decided to adopt a relatively more radical attitude, I indeed=20
now compose exclusively with free/open software mostly Pd and SC3 (in=20
order to be able to retrieve back my work on any computer). My attitude=20
goes further as after some debate that took place in France about open=20
software licences and peer to peer soft, I decided that the music that I=20
make should be released freely for everyone, as I believe that musicians=20
should only be paid for the performances they make, renewing with the=20
old age of music (when no recording was available) where musicians were=20
only able to make a living by giving "concerts" in order to sensitize=20
people with the fact that releasing albums is not a goal. This is also=20
highly justified by the fact that, even if I am using this kind of soft=20
for a while (about 1 year), I didn't really produce any tools for the=20
community (I would like to, but not enough code trained for the moment)=20
So, with respect for the very important people ;) that made it, I would=20
prefer to try making these tools get knowed by most than trying to claim=20
that I make all this music on my own, that I build my own music=20
software, blah, blah ... Artistically speaking, I am also very attracted=20
by getting the most out of the hardware. Because if we are here speaking=20
about software, and its paradigm, I think that we should never forget=20
that to run, it has to rely on very different types of hardware. So, I=20
am trying, as far as I can, to reach the boundaries of it, loving when=20
it acts in such an erratic way. I overall like to surprise the audience=20
by unexpected sounds, getting it away from the "I IV V I" scheme.
I am actualy a PhD student working on gestural control of speech=20
synthesis, so I am highly concerned about the way to control the music=20
produced by computers and also about the use of voices in my music. By=20
the way, I would love to be able to integrate what I do in my Phd into=20
my music, but have yet to work further for achieving it.
Anyhow, if you'd like to listen to a recent example of the music that I=20
make you can download a song here : www.myspace.com/rtheist . I know=20
myspace is surely not the best way for this, but was actually the=20
fastest and cheapest way to do it (as I am quite lazy...). I also join=20
the code used fot it (in lyrics part), made of parts of Synthdefs and=20
routines picked up in the examples of SC that I like most. This one is=20
made exclusively with SC3 and recorded live without any post treatment.=20
Don't hesitate to give me feedback on it.
Oh, I am also currently working with old friends of mine Vjs, try to set=20
up a more "classical" audiovisual performance.  But, I of course totally=20
agree with the toplap motto, and think I'll have the possibility to=20
discuss more about that now on this list ...

To follow
Best

Sylvain

