Date: Tue, 18 Apr 2006 11:07:42 +0200
From: douglas edric stanley <destanley
Subject: Re: [livecode] more new members


Howdy y'all!

I don't remember signing up on this list but I=20
suppose it's providence for two reasons:

1) I'm currently writing a doctoral thesis on=20
"abstract machines" which is more or less a=20
shortcut for algorithmic-based artwork, which is=20
another way of saying that everything Toplap is=20
doing is very cool and interrests me. I also met=20
Craig Latta last summer who went through the=20
whole process for me. And I'm a big fan of slub,=20
slab, whatever...

2) I've been doing what you call "livecoding" for=20
a little while now, not as long as most of you,=20
but for about two years or so. I didn't really=20
identify any of this practice with that term.

It actually first began as an accident. I was=20
VJ'ing with prepared algorithms for a DJ-soir=E9e=20
with a student of mine: we had about six=20
computers with as many videoprojectors covering=20
most of the walls. Bascially we were wallpaper,=20
as is often the case in these sort of settings.=20
About five minutes into the evening, a virus got=20
into the network and started fucking with the=20
machines. So we did as anyone would do, paniced,=20
ran around with-our-hair-on-fire=AE, and finally=20
gave up. So we decided to play with it, and=20
eventually began rebuilding the programs from=20
scratch as the night went on. At the time we were=20
using Director, so we would start with an asFFT=20
skeleton and program from there. Since we didn't=20
really care anymore at that point, we just left=20
the code up on the screen, and people got into=20
it. That gave us the idea to turn one of the text=20
actors into a programming console, stick it on=20
the stage, and with a key combination run it with=20
the "do" function in Lingo.

My stuents also mentioned last year how some of=20
my classes are a bit like a performance, so we=20
went with that idea and did a few semi-public=20
livecoding sessions at the end of one of our=20
workshops.

Nowadays, I usually do this as a part of a=20
presentation, where I begin or end it with a=20
performance. But come this december I'll be doing=20
a livecoding workshop in Mulhouse -- again as a=20
VJ'ing mechanism. Thanks to a recent post on the=20
Processing forum by Flo, I'll be using=20
Processing. We haven't figured out yet what to=20
use for the sound. I don't have the years of=20
experience coding Processing as I do with other=20
environments, so it'll probably be a learning=20
experience for myself as much as for the=20
participants.
-- 
