Date: Sun, 23 Apr 2006 17:14:51 +0100
From: Nick Collins <nc272
Subject: Re: [livecode] new members



For the (few)
> performances I've done with my students we set a time limit - 5 minutes -
> within which the performer has to put together a generative patch.
> A small Max patch running in the background crashes the computer after
> exactly 5 minutes of coding. This not only heightens the level of stress
> the performer experiences, resulting in a more invigorating experience
> for everybody, but it also ensures that the performer's work can't be
> saved, reflecting the transient (volatile?) nature of the medium.
>

This is great (especially the auto computer crash, reminds me of Alex's 
stage management techniques), I look forward to seeing a performance at 
some point.

I don't think there is a massive objection to Max per se, it's just 
probably not so powerful/convenient a programming language, but of course 
it is well suited to audio and has some built in audience accessibility.

I do wonder how much extra stress we could all take. Perhaps professional 
hecklers could be brought to live coding gigs, or hackers be allowed to 
disrupt a performer's system during a performance in efforts to shake them 
from their all consuming purpose...







Date: Sun, 23 Apr 2006 19:44:41 +0200
From: douglas edric stanley <destanley
Subject: Re: [livecode] new members


>This is great (especially the auto computer=20
>crash, reminds me of Alex's stage management=20
>techniques), I look forward to seeing a=20
>performance at some point.

I'd like to know more about "Alex's stage management techniques".

I recently built an automatic stage manager for=20
an interactive music/image/interactive hypertable=20
concert thingy I do with the group "8=3D8".

cf. http://www.abstractmachine.net/blog/?p=3D12

We called the program "Big_Daddy" because it runs=20
the show, not us -- the performers. It even=20
determines the start of the show, meaning that=20
performances start *on time*, down to the second.=20
It really is pleasant, and keeps things moving,=20
to have a program determining the order of the=20
sets and their lengths -- and not the lead=20
guitarist...

The question often with automatic conductors, is=20
how does the audience know about it? My collegues=20
from the group "PacJap" created a simple but=20
ingenious system that had a picture of each=20
participant in a big networked stream/mix/osc=20
whatever -- whenever someone contributed to the=20
flux, their picture lit up, or changed. Suddenly=20
you could understand who was doing what in the=20
performance.
-- 
