Subject: [livecode] cybersonica on may 19th/20th
From: alex <alex
Date: Sat, 13 May 2006 20:39:41 +0100



I was asked to make a panel for cybersonica in london and it's turned
into a TOPLAP panel; Amy, Nick and (so far not toplap affiliated but
livecoders) martin+jonni from ap/1010.

http://cybersonica.org/

The original plan was not to do something directly about livecoding but
that's what it's turned into.  Everything comes back to livecoding in
the end.

It's on Saturday 20th May from 11:30am until 1:30pm. 

Also we've got 40 mins worth of performance on 19th May.  There isn't a
fixed plan for what to do with that.  If anyone is around and wants to
join in some kind of jam please do, it might be fun to not use the
projectors and just have people dotted around so people can see the
screens, hub style.  Or maybe use the screens for the more visual stuff
(amy? dave?).  Anyway let me know if you're up for it and I'll work
something out.

Also, not livecoding related, but Amy is co-presenting her SVEN project
at dorkbotlondon at space studios in hackney on Wednesday the 24th.

Cheers,

alex




Date: Wed, 24 May 2006 10:35:14 +0100 (BST)
Subject: [livecode] livecoding with a gamepad
From: "Dave Griffiths" <dave


is the plan:
http://www.pawfal.org/index.php?page=3DClickCode

Very work in progress, but I'd like to make something that is easy to
write self modifying code live. the screenshot is the contents of memory
after a process has copied itself a few times, and wrapped around the 256
bytes of memory. It makes a lot more sense to see it in action, rather
than a snapshot.

orange =3D byte interpreted as an opcode
blue =3D byte used as data
red =3D byte being read from
yellow =3D byte being written to

It's sort of based on this: http://www.pawfal.org/Art/Quagmire/ but the
memory display will also be a simple IDE for the microcode, controllable
via ganepad/dance mat/joystick input :)

cheers,

dave



Date: Thu, 25 May 2006 16:37:24 +0100 (BST)
Subject: [livecode] xmeda
From: "Dave Griffiths" <dave


Hi all,

An online review of the xmedk workshop series in Brussels, containing
references to livecoding from Akihiro Kubota and myself, along with lots
of other related, and not so related interesting things:
http://www.xmeda.be/xmeda.screen.pdf

cheers,

dave



