> > > >>
> > > >>  which places do you mean? wired? trumpet? the net? the world?  :-)
> >
> > > >
> > > >I was thinking about the comments - in wired/slashdot etc, it is
> > always a
> > > >concept that seems to make a certain percentage of people angry.
> >
> > It's a shame the anger isn't directed at the tabloid journalism that
> > generates these sorts of stories. The article is full of inaccuracies,
> > misrepresentations and is, at best, one person's glossy intepretation of
> > something more substantial than the populist agenda it is pushing. I
> > suspect if the general Wired readership were aware of this such comments
> > wouldn't be so strong.
> >
> > Really... "traded in his guitar when he found he could be more creative
> > with code than with strings". Typical tabloidism.
> >
> > One of the great things about TOPLAP is that we can respond to this sort
> > of misrepresentation through ironic reflection. Our manifesto is
> > intentionally tongue-in-cheek to do exactly this. The same could be said
> >
> > of our non-commital acronym. These are weapons we should be using to
> > destroy the narrowminded casting of populist media. It's not like we
> > _need_ the acceptance of Wired's readership.
> >
> > I think we should form a TOPLAP Certification and Award scheme.
> > Certificates could be issued authoritatively to livecoding software to
> > reinforce the fact that livecoding is a thoroughly serious and important
> > facet of modern performance. Software producers would be able to apply
> > for
> > permission to TOPLAP to include the certification logo on software to
> > show
> > their compliance. Individuals could be rewarded to show how committed
> > they
> > are to the livecoding cause. It would be thoroughly important, and
> > include
> > lots of handwaving and backslapping. We'd write press releases, and
> > everything.
