>strategies of live codework, discursive=20
>hyperactivity, open artware development +=20
>extreme programming. this sessioning of=20
>theorypractices will crease, expand, infold,=20
>encode + translate variously interwoven=20
>[hacker/cracker] cultures to interrogate the=20
>elitism of "leet speek" as artspeak + artworld=20
>flirtations with naive outsider status in the=20
>formation of marketable artistic identities=20
>while pouring a warm bowl of welcoming milk for=20
>would be script kittens across distributed=20
>ports, applications + platforms. those who login=20
>to these conversational networks will=20
>{play|participate} in performative social=20
>constructions, commenting up contingent pseudo=20
>codes of temporary artware systems (i.e.=20
>Hyperyarn) + exploit scripts, criss-cross +=20
>cross-post on networks of meaning, bounce=20
>messages like balls of unspooling Hyperyarn +=20
>install online entanglements with a Duchampian=20
>Mile of String during ISEA 2006.
>
>As a Live Coding Environment, Hyperyarn includes=20
>a self-modifying source code editor, compiler,=20
>virtual machine + debugger with network support=20
>for collaborative + performative programming=20
>projects. Hyperyarn seeks to maintain strict=20
>Toplap compliancy as a Live Coding Environment=20
>by positioning Coding as a Conceptual Act of=20
>Social Artware. Congruent with strict Toplap=20
>compliancy standards, Hyperyans offers=20
>developers a conceptual coding environment to=20
>perform realtime artware development +=20
>[hacker/cracker/coder/artist/script kitty]=20
>identity constructions in realtime edge to edge=20
>autonmy + interdependence. Hyperyarn is written=20
>in Hyperyarn to increase self-reflexivity +=20
>recursiveness. Hyperyarn allows users to connect=20
>through insecure proxies during live coding=20
>sessions to further complicate + problematize=20
>assumptions + foreground conceptual artware=20
>instability, temporality + speculativity.=20
>Hyperyarn provides cross platform support for=20
>human computers, computational systems + mobile=20
>devices + is released under the GNU GPL.
>
>// begin recursion: 2006.08.11 13:00 PM CST
>// end recursion: ERROR: too much recursion


