Date: Sun, 27 Aug 2006 22:51:18 +0200
From: douglas edric stanley <destanley
Subject: Re: [livecode] book


I think it's a great idea. I would buy it!

There was a very inspiring book a few years back=20
by Friends of Ed called 4x4 Generative Design.=20
Many a student wore the binding down on that one=20
until it was just leaflets. You probably all know=20
of it as Adrian Ward was one of the authors, but=20
it was a sort of specialist book, probably not=20
very known outside of this list and their ilk. In=20
a similar vein, a couple different artists showed=20
their methods, each in his own chapter, then did=20
a mashup at the end of the book.

I probably wouldn't participate unless you wanted=20
a lame chapter on livecoding in Director (yawn),=20
but I couldn't think of a better group than this=20
one to come together and whip up something great.

If I wasn't reading this forum, I would be=20
writing about Livecoding right now for my thesis=20
(to be finished about the end of the year, or so=20
I claim), and there is already an editor=20
interrested in turning it into a book. But that=20
won't be started until next year, a bit late=20
probably. And that'll be just a chapter or two,=20
at best, and very theoretical, whereas what you=20
propose sounds far more hands-on, so far cooler.=20
And anyway I've got my own thing going and many=20
people even here probably won't agree with my=20
take on all this stuff.

As to the wiki/book conundrum, books are great=20
things. They are sort of historical stamps, and=20
have their own life parallel to - and not in=20
competition with - things like wikis. Also, wikis=20
have a hard time converging things tightly the=20
way books do. It's a limited space (only so many=20
pages) so people tend to make it matter. It also=20
requires an introduction - which wikis do very=20
poorly - giving people a quick access to the=20
essentials (try before you buy), which is=20
currently missing in the livecoding scene. And=20
obviously, any book on livecoding would have some=20
sort of wiki-thing associated with it.

My $0.05

Concerning Nick's comments:

>(Not sure live coding is sufficiently=20
>established to allow for a book yet, but then,=20
>perhaps the establishment is an outcome of=20
>creating a book! )

I think this is precisely the point. Usually=20
collective art books have a sort of manifesto=20
tinge to them, a sort of way of declaring that=20
something exists while contextualizing it. Also=20
it might be good to put something down before it=20
becomes something ugly, like what's happened to=20
VJ'ing. Usually if artists themselves don't do=20
it, no one will. Curators and art critics still=20
suck.

>Alternative possibilties might be a conference=20
>(with proceedings) on live coding. Or to=20
>actually hold the World Live Coding=20
>Championships.

I tried to get the ISEA/ZeroOne people into it=20
last summer, but they sort of yawned. I don't=20
think they fully got it. The Wired article might=20
have helped finding an audience...

>I did investigate with one academic journal=20
>about a special issue on live coding, though=20
>they could only guarantee space at the earliest=20
>in 2009. And the more widely distributed press=20
>articles are a better promotion if that is the=20
>main aim of writing.


>I was wondering if anyone's thought of writing a book about livecoding.
>Either way, is it a good idea?  My initial thought was that we could put
>together a proposal to o'reilly as an excercise, and if they don't
>accept it go ahead anyway, perhaps as a wikibook.
>
>I don't know if it would really fit into o'reilly's series but I'm
>thinking an introductory chapter about each of the main systems, a
>chapter on the theory of interactive programming, a chapter about the
>technicalities of doing so in a range of languages, a bit about cutting
>edge livecoding techniques - use of history, the blurring between code
>and GUI and so on...  So instructive but still with plenty room for
>humour.
>
>On one hand a publisher like O'Reilly won't like a proposal with more
>than a few authors, and on the other a wikibook should have as many as
>possible...  So we see who's interested I guess.
>
>On the other hand maybe this is a bad/old fashioned idea and we should
>just stick with the wikis we already have.  I just think it might be
>something fun to work towards.
