Subject: Re: [livecode] language for conversational computing
From: alex <alex
Date: Thu, 21 Sep 2006 00:41:52 +0100


On Thu, 2006-09-21 at 00:07 +0200, Julian Rohrhuber wrote:
> that sounds very interesting. what makes this language more 
> conversational than others?

Some more about it here:

http://hopl.murdoch.edu.au/showlanguage2.prx?exp=228

It seems it was a precursor to smalltalk, and is properly known as LC
squared.

LC2 seems a good search term, leading to this interesting paper
"building dynamic programs" by Peter Brown:
  http://historical.ncstrl.org/litesite-data/stan/CS-TR-81-838.pdf

I like the idea of a program having "loose ends" that a programmer fills
in while it's running, and then running a checker that makes sure that
the loose ends are tied up before passing the finished program on to the
end user.

alex




Date: Thu, 21 Sep 2006 09:38:29 +0100 (BST)
Subject: Re: [livecode] language for conversational computing
From: "Dave Griffiths" <dave


> On Thu, 2006-09-21 at 00:07 +0200, Julian Rohrhuber wrote:
>> that sounds very interesting. what makes this language more
>> conversational than others?
>
> Some more about it here:
>
> http://hopl.murdoch.edu.au/showlanguage2.prx?exp=3D228
>
> It seems it was a precursor to smalltalk, and is properly known as LC
> squared.
>
> LC2 seems a good search term, leading to this interesting paper
> "building dynamic programs" by Peter Brown:
>   http://historical.ncstrl.org/litesite-data/stan/CS-TR-81-838.pdf
>
> I like the idea of a program having "loose ends" that a programmer fill=
s
> in while it's running, and then running a checker that makes sure that
> the loose ends are tied up before passing the finished program on to th=
e
> end user.

this sounds a bit like the test driven programming method, where you writ=
e
the all the tests first (sometimes this is done by another programmer),
then when all the tests pass you've finished. this is the reverse of how
most people do it, but it's much more effective.

loose ends has a much nicer sound to it though :)

I cant find LC2 on this, but it might be a good time to send it round
again anyway:
http://www.oreilly.com/pub/a/oreilly/news/languageposter_0504.html

cheers,

dave



Date: Thu, 21 Sep 2006 10:56:04 +0200
From: Julian Rohrhuber <rohrhuber
Subject: Re: [livecode] language for conversational computing


>On Thu, 2006-09-21 at 00:07 +0200, Julian Rohrhuber wrote:
>>  that sounds very interesting. what makes this language more
>>  conversational than others?
>
>Some more about it here:
>
>http://hopl.murdoch.edu.au/showlanguage2.prx?exp=228



this seems to be almost a full description of interactive programming:



	1.	The program text, being under direct execution, is 
understood to be "immediately" subject to change and hence the system 
statements, known as editing statements, are part of the language. 
Put another way, the text is data of the language.
	2.	The order of text entry, i.e., its creation, need not 
be as rigid as that required by most translation systems; indeed, the 
order is irrelevant.
	3.	The scope of identifiers and the definition of a 
procedure can be much more dynamic.
	4.	The states of program modification and execution can 
be interlaced flexibly.
	5.	Program variables may naturally take on values of 
different types during different stages of execution.
	6.	The system can arrange the execution of program parts 
in protected environments.
-- 





.


Date: Thu, 21 Sep 2006 11:27:06 +0200
From: Julian Rohrhuber <rohrhuber
Subject: Re: [livecode] language for conversational computing


a propos the recent discussion about tolerant languages etc: 
conversational lisp (CLISP, 1973) had the objective to be more 
flexible in this way:

http://community.computerhistory.org/scc/projects/LISP/interlisp/Teitelman-3IJCAI.pdf
