yes, that was my issue with the lsystem rule coding for a while - but on
further research (mainly the formal rules as arithmetic processor in
Godel Escher Bach) it seems that even the simplest domain specific
languages can be used to express much higher level things.

> I've tried to perform with it twice and not had much luck...  I'd like
> to persevere though if you + ade are up for it!

... and it worked very well too to my ears...

for the record I livecoded some audio controlled procedural geometry
defined using turtle operations. very satisfying as it was all from
scratch and I didn't save the script :)

cheers,

dave



From: Fredrik Olofsson <f
Subject: Re: [livecode] livecoding with a bp2-alike thing
Date: Mon, 27 Nov 2006 02:18:25 +0100


hi alex.
er, with sc i think you'll need to create the glitches yourself ;-)  
emulation?  top of this page is an ugen and a class that might help...
http://www.fredrikolofsson.com/pages/code-sc.html
no seriously, sc server is a hard one to trick.  allocating big chunks 
of memory will get you some hickups but not particularly interesting as 
glitches.  on os x the server is pretty hard to crash i found.
(sc lang on the other hand has a lot to offer.  eg just opening 
helpfiles or sorting big arrays makes the timing (AppClock) all shaky.  
but you only run sc server, right?)

nice screencast btw.  keep them coming!  looking forward to seeing it 
live.
_f


