From: "zuzu (sean)" <sean.zuzu
Subject: Re: [livecode] more livecoding movies
Date: Sat, 7 Apr 2007 14:08:56 -0400


This is an OpenPGP/MIME signed message (RFC 2440 and 3156)
--Apple-Mail-127-93641913
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 7bit
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=US-ASCII; delsp=yes; format=flowed

On 4/4/07, Dave Griffiths <dave@hiddenorg> wrote:
 > hi all,
 >
 > I've "youtubed" a load of old livecoding movies here:
 > http://www.pawfal.org/dave/movies.html
 >
 > cheers,
 >
 > dave

Thanks!

can you paste the URLs for the originals which aren't in FLV format?

or, if they're original to you but you can't afford the the bandwidth  
to host them, would you please also upload them to Revver and/or the  
Internet Archive (archive.org)?

I appreciate that YouTube provides "easy access", but IMHO flash- 
based players suck to interact with.  (It all goes back to that paper  
circa 2002 saying that Flash/Shockwave is the most deployed web  
browser plugin, and it also happens to encapsulate video, so if you  
were trying to avoid the QuickTime Sorenson vs. Real Media vs.  
Windows Media format war, it was the way to go.)  However, now that  
Quicktime supports MPEG-4 by default, and MPEG-4 is a mostly open  
standard (without getting into the Xiph / patents tangent), I'm not  
sure why FLV still gains momentum as a defacto format.  (Especially  
since VideoLAN so far can't seek within FLV, AFAIK.)

thanks again,
-sean

