Subject: [livecode] live/life coding
From: alex <alex
Date: Sun, 19 Aug 2007 23:19:58 +0100



An interesting programming language running on irc:
http://esoteric.voxelperfect.net/wiki/IRP

the problem being it got a bit popular via a post to
programming.reddit.com, so the interpreters on the irc channel are
really grumpy.

An interesting wiki, anyway :)



Date: Mon, 20 Aug 2007 01:32:29 +0200
From: Julian Rohrhuber <rohrhuber
Subject: Re: [livecode] live/life coding


>An interesting programming language running on irc:
>http://esoteric.voxelperfect.net/wiki/IRP
>
>the problem being it got a bit popular via a post to
>programming.reddit.com, so the interpreters on the irc channel are
>really grumpy.
>
>An interesting wiki, anyway :)


ha!
solving recursion problems by boredom is a very modern approach 
indeed: "The only real problem with a quine in this format is that it 
could easily lead to infinite recursion, until the interpreters get 
bored." The boredom parameter should be part of any indeterministic 
system.

-- 





.


Date: Mon, 20 Aug 2007 10:45:58 +0100
From: Matthew Yee-King <lists
Subject: Re: [livecode] ascii rave


he doesn't theorise it in terms of live coding and the possibilties you
>> show in the video, but it might be worth referencing? He uses a DIY speech 
>> synthesis approach like you that gives speech with (uncanny?) character, 
>> having spent a long obsessive time himself mapping out English phones...
> 
> Ace!  I'm a real stickler for obsessive mapping although my own mapping
> only took about 10 minutes, I just used a mouse to pick values for the
> two parameters that were a bit like each consonant.  

I have this genetic algorithm based system with which I might be able to
search for some good settings if you send me the synthdef... it can
iteratively update the settings as they improve - is that live coding??
I need to get another paper out of it then I can GPL it.

cheers

- matthew


Subject: Re: [livecode] ascii rave
From: alex <alex
Date: Mon, 20 Aug 2007 23:44:25 +0100


On Mon, 2007-08-20 at 10:45 +0100, Matthew Yee-King wrote:
> > Ace!  I'm a real stickler for obsessive mapping although my own mapping
> > only took about 10 minutes, I just used a mouse to pick values for the
> > two parameters that were a bit like each consonant.  
