Date: Sun, 02 Sep 2007 18:18:48 +0100
From: Nick Collins <nc272
Subject: [livecode] full slate live coding


here's a little something which Andrew, Andrew and I were discussing over 
dinner this week.

Rather than starting from a blank slate, you could begin with as much code 
as you're ever going to write. Then your task is to gradually delete 
instructions (like a game of jenga?). Perhaps you'd deconstruct, perhaps 
you'd destroy and subvert. But you might end the set by deleting the last 
consequential command and thus bring visualisation, audio or vibrotactile 
olfactoriness to an end.

This can of course dovetail with blank slate coding, indeed, the two can go 
in waves. Perhaps a timer controls the process and participants first build 
up, then down, swapping the hot seat.

A breakpoint envelope/control function might determine swap times and 
changes being creation and destruction. A up B down, B up, A down might 
form one variant. And so forth...

Plus, all the participants would wear waistcoats and stroke their chins as 
their opponent moved matters to tricky positions.






 


Date: Sun, 02 Sep 2007 19:50:34 +0200
From: Sylvain <artheist
Subject: Re: [livecode] full slate live coding


Hi Nick,

Nick Collins a =E9crit :
> here's a little something which Andrew, Andrew and I were discussing=20
> over dinner this week.
>
> Rather than starting from a blank slate, you could begin with as much=20
> code as you're ever going to write. Then your task is to gradually=20
> delete instructions (like a game of jenga?).=20
ITAWT, and btw I was discussing of this with Julian (and maybe andrew=20
... ) in Sheffield which is made possible more easily with this history=20
'timemachine' Julian presented.
More Deeply, I think this scope allows from escaping from the=20
conventional compositional practice that builds songs like layers over=20
layers and puts climax at its end ...
> Perhaps you'd deconstruct, perhaps you'd destroy and subvert. But you=20
> might end the set by deleting the last consequential command and thus=20
> bring visualisation, audio or vibrotactile olfactoriness to an end.
>
> This can of course dovetail with blank slate coding, indeed, the two=20
> can go in waves. Perhaps a timer controls the process and participants=20
> first build up, then down, swapping the hot seat.
>
> A breakpoint envelope/control function might determine swap times and=20
> changes being creation and destruction. A up B down, B up, A down=20
> might form one variant. And so forth...
>
> Plus, all the participants would wear waistcoats and stroke their=20
> chins as their opponent moved matters to tricky positions.
>
>
I don't really know if I understood your exemple very well, but here is=20
another idea (which I hope corroborate yours)
You can also imagine a chessboard reprensenting 16 processes for two=20
players, like this : Rook =3D bass drum, Knight =3D Snare, Bishop =3D Hi-=
Hat,=20
Queen =3D Melody, King =3D On/Off, Pawns =3D Polyphony
So, anytime you move a piece, a process begin (according to the=20
polyphony determined by pawns), then the X/Y place of the piece could be=20
the pitch and bpm. Anytime you eat a piece you gain either polyphony or=20
a defined synth, etc .. (I think you got the point to build up new rules)
Then the time swaps you are talking about would be determined by each tur=
n.
And, of course, this can be visualized with Fluxus ;D

My two cents

Sylvain
>
>
>
>
>



