Date: Thu, 3 Jan 2008 15:49:01 +0100
From: douglas edric stanley <destanley
Subject: Re: [livecode] non-linguistic programming


Hi Alex.

>  > Of note: I call them text-based languages because
>>  I think (as I describe in the paper) that they
>>  have very little to do with language, and have
>>  everything to do with the way in which ASCII is
>>  represented within the machine.
>
>I do not fully understand your argument, I think I'm missing
>something...  A novel is a list of characters in the same way that a
>text based program is.

Ok, there are several responses to this. I can't get to them all here.

=46or me a novel is not just a list of characters.=20
Just as a picture is something far more than a=20
mere string of pixels in an array. The internal=20
mechanics of a novel's representation inside of a=20
computer is merely an exploit, a hack, that=20
computer science has found, although a handy one=20
at that. But just because a novel can be=20
represented inside of a computer through an=20
array, and a picture can be represented inside of=20
a computer through an array, this does not mean=20
that novels and pictures are nothing more than=20
strung-together tokens. I think this is quite=20
obvious. They might be so in a computer, but that=20
is merely a problem of representation, and even=20
worse, a mere representation within the computer=20
architecture.

So if you'll follow me on this train of thought,=20
there is no real fundamental difference in=20
programming via characters inside of a char *=20
array, and pixels inside of an int * array. We=20
only have to look at The Game of Life, or=20
SimTunes, of some of Dave Griffiths examples=20
previously listed here, in order to see that you=20
can very well program with tokens of all sorts. I=20
created a video-mosiac-programming-language a few=20
years back to illustrate something along these=20
lines. There are many other examples. I think,=20
like others here, that games are probably the=20
wave of the future on the question of programming=20
and its representation.

To get back to my original observation: the=20
special thing about character-based programming=20
is that the trick is almost readable. I say=20
almost, because most people can't figure out what=20
the fuck is going on. For example, I'm writing a=20
lot of C++ right now, and in that language you=20
can write a lot of fascinating obfuscations like=20
this:

for(char*i=3D"Hello"; *i!=3D'\0'; ++i) std::cout << *i << std::endl;

I'm sorry to offend all the robots out there, but=20
that's totally unreadable unless you understand=20
the underlying architecture of the computer. You=20
have to understand memory addresses and pointers=20
and loops and streams, etc. This is not writing,=20
has nothing to do with literature, etc. This is=20
more like knitting. So my real question is: if we=20
are already kitting, why not just knit?

Which returns me to the question of beauty. I'm=20
sorry, but code is ugly. Knitting is beautiful,=20
coding is ugly. Sure, I absolutely love the above=20
C++ code, I find it -- gasp -- kind of lovely, at=20
least fascinating. But it's still very geeky and=20
bastardly, i.e. ugly in the etymological sense:=20
it's dreadful. I'm assuming that most of us here=20
can read/write several computer languages, and=20
therefore can see the structure, the machines,=20
behind this code. So suddenly it becomes=20
something else. But not because of the glyph. The=20
glyph is only a token, I want to say=20
"un-signe-quelconque" in hommage to Deleuze's=20
"instants-quelconques".

It can be rendered fascinating, lovely,=20
beautiful, whatever -- but you have to transform=20
it into a performance, re-render it into an=20
aesthetic form, etc. -- and play with the fact=20
that a computer glyph changes the use-value of=20
the more historical glyph. I suppose that's why I=20
love Livecoding as a sort of artistic manifesto.=20
The art-hack of livecoding is a very novel=20
response to the computer science hack of char *=20
arrays. It uses the constructs of art-performance=20
to redefine code itself, by revealing something=20
in the code that talks to artists, as if it were=20
always there in the code to begin with. It also=20
speaks to the history of glyphs. That's pretty=20
damn impressive in my book, but it still doesn't=20
hide the fact that text-based coding is merely a=20
hack and could replaced by all sorts of other=20
forms of representation.

All that said, I love to code and I love to look=20
at it. I think it's quite amazing. I'm also=20
fascinated with this historical hack of=20
associating the physical keyboard array with the=20
char * array with the programming stack. But I=20
cannot for the life of me see how people can keep=20
coding like this, i.e. from the perspective of=20
the history of human representations.

There is nothing moral in these arguments. I'm=20
not saying code is ugly in the sense that code is=20
"bad". I'm just saying that it's historically=20
curious, and in my opinion will transform into=20
something more historically profound. Hence=20
knitting, music, mosaics, who-knows...

>   I don't see why this linearity leads to
>ugliness.

Well, I don't know if that's what I was trying to=20
suggest. I just think that historically=20
text-based programming facilitated to an amazing=20
degree modularity and abstraction, thanks to all=20
of the modularity and abstraction already=20
inherent in text systems. Text is also linear, as=20
was the Turing Machine -- hence the alliance=20
between the two -- but both of them are far more=20
than that, too. So it's a mere alliance, like all=20
alliances, of convienence. But their achitectures=20
cannot be reduced to mere linearity. Computation=20
does not need text to survive. Let us not confuse=20
the two.

And so it seems quite revealing to me that the=20
text-computation pact would truly begin to show=20
its cracks at precisely the moment when we are=20
forced to work with multiple processors, threads,=20
etc. in order to evolve. The processor speed wall=20
has been good at revealing this problem.

I think it's also significant that many artists=20
use Max/PureData and all their cousins (vvvv,=20
EyesWeb, etc) without any trouble and do some=20
pretty amazing things with them. This leads us=20
back to the original Google talk.

I think it's an important question to ask, even=20
if we never get past it: was historically tying=20
linear text-string-of-perls the best way to=20
represent computation?

>Are pure functional programs immune from your criticism?

I don't know. I'll have to think about that.

>   For example
>Haskell programs are not sequences of instructions (leaving aside
>monadic trickery) and so functions may be executed in any order,
>concurrently across any number of processors.

Yes, that's a very cool concept.

>  They are however
>represented in ASCII, with two dimensional structure (linefeeds and
>whitespace have meaning).

Haskell is still pretty unreadable, therefore a=20
bit of a kludge. But at least it looks unreadable=20
from the get-go and doesn't pretend otherwise.=20
But you have to be a computer scientist to read=20
it, whereas I'm going in the other direction.=20
Anyone can learn to play puzzles and knit, so I=20
think that's a far richer direction to explore.

I always wonder about Lisp. It seems to me to be a largely overlooked langua=
ge.
-- 
