>>representations.
>
>Well, maybe for the same reason they stopped=20
>using an abacus for everything and developed=20
>symbolic algebra?

Point taken. But whenever I program these=20
machines, I feel like I'm stuck back in the days=20
of using an abacus.

>there is nothing inherently linear about text,

Oh, absolutely. But most text-based programming=20
languages run like a string of perls inside of=20
the machine.

>just as there is nothing non-interactive about a=20
>book. You can read in what ever way you like.

Sure. But that's in part the power of the spine,=20
not of the string of characters on the page. But=20
you are absolutely right that text does not have=20
to be linear. Text is also used in tax ledgers,=20
which is obviously not just a linear collection=20
of words, and can be read in many directions.=20
Text can be used for many different things. This=20
is one of the reasons it's so efficient for=20
programming, as opposed to boxes and lines.
