> Yawn. Suggesting that I'm just arguing from the position of
> ignorance? Nice one. I figured someone would try that. But I stand by
> it nevertheless. My argument was a little more subtle than that,
> thankyouverymuch.

I'm trying to follow this, and I'm not sure I agree with your arguments -
but I do agree with the spirit of what you are saying.

I think at issue is not so much individual languages, but the philosophie=
s
they represent. I think it's fair to say that functional languages are th=
e
closest to mathematics - and it's also fair to blame mathematicians for a
lot of unreadability ;) but this unreadability and "un-naturalness" is fo=
r
a reason. I read this yesterday, which I think is appropriate:
http://www.vex.net/~trebla/weblog/common.html

I think this argument usually comes up, not because of aesthetic reasons,
but because there is a feeling that programming is hard, we are not very
good at it, and there must be ways of improving the situation.

Ironically, haskell is a language which tries very hard to make
programming easier and safer (by constraining what you can do).

cheers,

dave



Date: Fri, 4 Jan 2008 10:35:19 +0100
From: "Artem Baguinski" <artm
Subject: Re: [livecode] non-linguistic programming


On 1/3/08, douglas edric stanley <destanley@hiddencom> wrote:

> text-based programming has very little to do with linguistics.

programming languages are called that because they share *some*
properties with natural languages: they exist to create and
communicate meaning. they indeed would be uninteresting subjects to a
natural linguistics scholar, but that's why programming linguistics
exists.

languages don't exist to write literature, but are used by artists to
do that nevertheless. using natural language to tell stories that
never happened, to envoke emotions and sketch landscapes was a sort of
hackery - misusing tool that was used to communicate about reality -
but eventually these new uses transformed the language and the mind of
its users.

code doesn't exist to be beautiful, but often nevertheless is - like
landscapes or faces [*]. to appreciate it though you've got to
understand what it's doing and often - guess why it is written the way
it is. but i guess understanding alone is not enough for appreciation
- you've got to respect the medium to see beautiful code.

[*] from evolutionary point of view one of important goals of the face
is to be attractive. using beauty for art is another hack that artists
perform. beauty of code helps it survive (as obfuscated c code contest
shows - code that from enginering point of view shouldn't exist gets
archived and mirrored on http://www.ioccc.org/ due to its perceived
beauty) wether this beauty is artificial (intended) or natural.

Understanding and cultivating that what makes code beautiful is what
"text-based" coding artforms are about.

-- 
cheers,
artm

http://lab.v2.nl/


