Date: Fri, 04 Jan 2008 12:30:28 +0000
From: rob
Subject: Re: [livecode] non-linguistic programming


Quoting Dave Griffiths <dave@hiddenorg>:

> Ironically, haskell is a language which tries very hard to make
> programming easier and safer (by constraining what you can do).

There's the execution model and then there's the syntax.

Haskell has an excellent execution model with all sorts of functional =20
and type-based goodness. Likewise, Perl has brilliant regexps and IO =20
facilities. They then wrap this in syntax that looks like line noise.

JavaScript and Dylan are basically Lisps (at the execution model =20
level) with C and Algol syntax respectively. Lua looks like Dylan but =20
is hashtable based rather than using the CLOS object system. Python is =20
Perl for the fearful.

There is rarely any causal link between execution model and syntax or =20
representation. I'd be much happier with a PD or Max that used text =20
rather than 1984-era QuickDraw boxes, and I prefer Python to Perl =20
because of the syntax.

But...

A good heuristic is "change the notation".

With Lisp I started out with Dylan, which as I mentioned is an =20
Algol-syntax language (think Pascal or Lua if you don't know Algol). I =20
have moved slowly to Common Lisp, which has Lots of Irritating Silly =20
Parentheses. The Lisp syntax is both addictive for hacking in and a =20
useful thing for writing tools to work with code. So some syntaxes are =20
more useful for some things for others, oven if they represent the =20
same execution model behind the scenes.

This site is good for syntax comparisons (and sometimes execution =20
model comparisons):

http://99-bottles-of-beer.net/

- Rob.




Subject: Re: [livecode] non-linguistic programming
From: alex <alex
Date: Fri, 04 Jan 2008 12:50:22 +0000



On Fri, 2008-01-04 at 12:30 +0000, rob@hiddenorg wrote:
> There's the execution model and then there's the syntax.
> 
> Haskell has an excellent execution model with all sorts of functional  
> and type-based goodness. Likewise, Perl has brilliant regexps and IO  
> facilities. They then wrap this in syntax that looks like line noise.

I agree the array/scalar/hash context stuff can make Perl look ugly,
until you're familiar enough with it to be able to see through it.  And
the inbuilt regex (being largely a language of icons rather than words)
looks ugly from being so dense (the /x modifier helps).  

But what in the syntax of haskell do you find ugly?  To me, the syntax
is incredibly clean and well defined.

> There is rarely any causal link between execution model and syntax or  
> representation. 

Yes good point.  I think to the trained eye, the aesthetics of language
syntax matter much less than that of the semantics.

I was reading a nice mailing list post by a lisp person (sorry can't
remember where) saying that they stopped 'seeing' the brackets after a
day or so of learning lisp, and that people who complain about brackets
in lisp should also complain about whitespace in all other languages.

alex




Date: Fri, 4 Jan 2008 13:15:49 -0000 (GMT)
Subject: Re: [livecode] non-linguistic programming
From: "Dave Griffiths" <dave



>
> On Fri, 2008-01-04 at 12:30 +0000, rob@hiddenorg wrote:
>> There's the execution model and then there's the syntax.
