when I talked about Little Big Planet being a=20
model for programming computers.

>Plus elements of that old game called "the incredible machine"
><http://youtube.com/watch?v=3DNdtGXBQLNTw>http://youtube.com/watch?v=3DNdtG=
XBQLNTw

There was a great game that I wrote about several=20
years back. I always loved it. It was a game=20
translated in France as "Eur=EAka", I think it's=20
called "Widget Workshop" originally. Published by=20
Maxis if I remember.

I always loved TIM as well. Great stuff. It=20
actually inspired me for my Game Machine project,=20
where you could program classic games purely by=20
drag & drop. Old project. I don't know if I have=20
any decent documentation on that. When I was=20
designing it, several of my students showed me=20
things that went in a similar direction in all=20
the games I missed in the 90's. One of them was a=20
very interesting communication system with=20
symbols -- hmmm, can't remember the name. But all=20
of them were too tied to one specific task,=20
whereas TIM and Widget Studio were more=20
open-ended. Plus you could make a cow moo by=20
connecting it to the rhythm of a beating mouse=20
heart. Can't get any better than that.
