Date: Mon, 7 Jan 2008 21:24:42 +0100
From: douglas edric stanley <destanley
Subject: Re: [livecode] non-linguistic programming


As for the idea of skipping the machine,=20
obviously (cf. my website) I just can't follow=20
you on that one. Although, sure, we could clearly=20
hide all sorts of processes in any phenomenon,=20
and treat all sorts of things like black boxes,=20
but do we want to, and can anything become an=20
abstraction but merely ignoring/avoiding it?  I=20
would suggest not, and would even suggest that it=20
can lead us down a path of denial (Verdr=E4ngung).

Again, to a certain extent, I could follow you on=20
that path, because indeed, part of looking at=20
things algorithmically is looking beyond the=20
machine as mere mechanics. But I honestly think=20
you need to redefine the machine and it's role as=20
an ensemble, rather than as a pure means to and=20
end. No machine is mere means. It's a thought=20
process, and is indistinguishable with the=20
thinking it provokes. I figure that on a=20
livecoding list what I've just said is obvious.=20
But maybe I've misunderstood.

Anyway, music without instruments and musicians=20
is just as absurd as music without music. That's=20
probably why Wittgenstein was the only=20
appropriate response.

>In a real-world sense we can think about this=20
>occurring when an experienced=20
>composer/conductor/performer reads and "hears" a=20
>musical score purely cerebrally.  This process=20
>completely skips the "machine" (i.e. the=20
>instruments and players) and moves directly from=20
>the symbol system to a mental reification of the=20
>abstractions defined by the score.  In short,=20
>the composer becomes able to fluently translate=20
>between the symbol system (the score) and the=20
>task domain (the sounds of the orchestra)=20
>thereby avoiding the machine (the players and=20
>instruments of the orchestra) altogether.

-- 
