From: Andrew Sorensen <andrew
Subject: Re: [livecode] non-linguistic programming
Date: Tue, 8 Jan 2008 11:00:58 +1000


> As for the idea of skipping the machine, obviously (cf. my website) =20=

> I just can't follow you on that one. Although, sure, we could =20
> clearly hide all sorts of processes in any phenomenon, and treat all =20=

> sorts of things like black boxes, but do we want to, and can =20
> anything become an abstraction but merely ignoring/avoiding it?  I =20
> would suggest not, and would even suggest that it can lead us down a =20=

> path of denial (Verdr=E4ngung).

Who said anything about ignoring or avoiding?  In my example the =20
machine was not ignored or avoided, it was deemed unnecessary.  Of =20
course what makes all of this seem ridiculous is the practicality of =20
someone becoming so fluent that the machine could become superfluous.  =20=

But it is none-the-less interesting to consider.

> Again, to a certain extent, I could follow you on that path, because =20=

> indeed, part of looking at things algorithmically is looking beyond =20=

> the machine as mere mechanics. But I honestly think you need to =20
> redefine the machine and it's role as an ensemble, rather than as a =20=

> pure means to and end. No machine is mere means. It's a thought =20
> process, and is indistinguishable with the thinking it provokes. I =20
> figure that on a livecoding list what I've just said is obvious. But =20=

> maybe I've misunderstood.

Well, of course I agree with you that all tools have a huge influence =20=

on thought and computers are certainly tools. However, tools are also =20=

generally causal, and for these tools (causal ones) it is usually =20
their experiential results that effect our thought.  I would place =20
codes execution on a machine in this causal tool category.  =20
Mathematics, however, is a good example of a tool that is not causal - =20=

it's effect on our thought is reasoned not experiential.  When we get =20=

to program code things get more tricky.  Most programmers of course =20
balk at the notion of non-causal code (i.e. code that is never =20
actually run on a machine), because it seems obtuse to talk of code =20
that has no causal effect.  So to get back to your comment you are =20
assuming that code requires a machine to be "useful" - or put another =20=

way you are making a statement that only causal outcomes are a valid =20
use of program code.

> Anyway, music without instruments and musicians is just as absurd as =20=

> music without music. That's probably why Wittgenstein was the only =20
> appropriate response.

So you've never been on a long walk with an ABBA song running around =20
your head?



From: Andrew Sorensen <andrew
Subject: Re: [livecode] non-linguistic programming
Date: Tue, 8 Jan 2008 11:08:17 +1000


Actually I was just trying to get to the bottom of Julians email, so  
frankly I blame him for this mess!

But while I'm here :)

> That's interesting. I agree that one can read music like this, but  
> would we
> call it "listening"? So the question is about your word (in  
> quotations) "hear"
> here. These are two different ways of using the word "hear".

Hearing is of course a physical phenomenon, so I'm not really trying  
to suggest that "inner hearing" is the same as "external hearing" but  
this is not to deny that it exists, that we make use of it, and,  
importantly for this conversation, that it can be pleasurable.  Just  
lie back on the couch, close your eyes, and transport yourself to a  
tropical island listening to gamelan :)

> I'm reminded of Wittgenstein's passage on playing mental chess and
> mental tennis. He seems to think both are possible, but for me the  
> former
> makes sense and not the latter.

Well, I would agree that mental tennis is not real tennis but I  
wouldn't say that it doesn't make sense.  Bob sled drivers for example  
are well known for spending hours mentally visualizing their descents  
in preparation for the actual run.  But I'll stop being contrary and  
say that I agree with you in principle :)

> If live-coding is about the relationship between the program and the  
> task-
> domain, it becomes a "formal art" like Chess. The sound is a  
> "representation"
> of the thought, just like the chessboard and pieces are merely a  
> tool for
> extended cognition (external representation) and not a necessary  
> part of
> the game.
>
> As a musician are you happy with that conclusion?

Nope, not happy at all.  I want to hear it all with my external ears  
bleeding and my external chest thumping :)

> smack smack : )

And justifiably so, I promise to be quiet now :)


Date: Tue, 8 Jan 2008 22:45:14 +0100
From: douglas edric stanley <destanley
Subject: Re: [livecode] non-linguistic programming


>So to get back to your comment you are assuming=20
>that code requires a machine to be "useful" - or=20
>put another way you are making a statement that=20
>only causal outcomes are a valid use of program=20
>code.

Well no, I wouldn't make that statement, because=20
obviously you /can/ write pseudo-code and it=20
still makes sense. But it is still a part of the=20
machinic process. It is an activity in relation=20
to machines and to execution stacks, so even if=20
pseudo-code needs no machine, it is still a=20
machinic diagram, i.e. part of a machinic=20
apparatus. Machinic thinking, if you will.

Which indeed, I agree with you, distinguishes it somewhat to mathematics.

>>Anyway, music without instruments and musicians=20
>>is just as absurd as music without music.=20
>>That's probably why Wittgenstein was the only=20
>>appropriate response.
>
>So you've never been on a long walk with an ABBA=20
>song running around your head?

Oh sure. Steigler has some interresting things to=20
say about that, by the way, if you're=20
interrested. But that would lead us a bit too=20
much off subject.

Still, the music in your head is instrumental.=20
And a melody that you hum along to yourself is=20
even all the more instrumental. It's your body=20
that actualizes the melody. As does your=20
consciousness, even if you don't actually make=20
any noise. This is pretty basic hermeneutics.=20
Husserl would be the starting point, and his=20
writings on temporal retention in relation to the=20
temporality of consciousness.
-- 
