> Agreed, recursivity would be a starting point for me, too. Now what
> about this: Assume you have a game where your first person movements
> depend on the environment, and you may change this environment with
> your actions. If you interpret this situation in terms of the
> environment as the machine in the machine, then you are building /
> modifying a new machine by your actions. But it is a standard
> situation for a game, so nothing special at all.

I would say that case is not so interesting because the landscape only ha=
s
meaning for the player - i.e. it's not a machine in itself.

Where it gets harder is if there is an AI bot which interprets the
environment, now you are modifying something which is changing the
behaviour of a machine, a bit more interesting. A possible distinction is
that it doesn't _define_ the bot's behaviour (it's analogous to it's set
of parameters). If it did, this would be livecoding for me.

> Then we have the choice: Live coding is something like a subjective
> decision to regard this action as such, or to find a more essential
> difference.

It seems that it's subjective what a programming language is, so it might
be hard to move further - but I think "total definition of something's
behaviour" points to something, maybe. The level of built in abstraction
makes this harder to pin down, and is a sort of continuum - in the same
way as livecoding from prewritten scripts or lots of predefined functions
seems to make the case weaker (to the point of a function called
"PlayMyLivecodingTrack();")

> One possibility is to characterize live coding by its
> distance from physical modeling, by its character of being involved
> with the formal, or axiomatic. So  I think Swami Fadereu is right if
> he refers to the sundial and to interaction as an example to pose the
> same question. I agree that abstraction is an essential
> characteristic here. But of course I am curious to see other views.

I think a definition of a machine for a machine to interpret must be
axiomatic (almost by erm, definition?).

I'm getting confused now, I need to read more about these sundials...

cheers,

dave



Date: Wed, 9 Jan 2008 13:56:10 +0100
From: Kassen <signal.automatique
Subject: Re: [livecode] non-linguistic programming


------=_Part_47719_26635118.1199883371061
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=ISO-8859-1
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 7bit
Content-Disposition: inline

On 09/01/2008, AlgoMantra <algomantra@hiddencom> wrote:
>
>
> Even a traditional instrument, like say a guitar - it's interface or map
> is somewhat visible as the fretboard, though the 'playing program' is
> clearly
> embedded within the player's own muscle-memory. The harmonica on
> the other hand is nearly invisible.
>

Yes, I agree. Te extend this;

If I were a band leader or some sort of conductor I might instruct my
pianist to play C3, then G4, then.... or I might instruct him to play a
arpeggio going up along a certain chord. These two instructions are on a
different level. A pianist who plays a rapid series of notes isn't actually
instructing his body to do this note by note, he has trained his muscle
memory, in a way he has, by practicing, re-programed himself. (it would be
interesting to wonder whether Thelonious Monk programed in a different
"language" then a concert pianist learning to play Liszt).

Livecoding makes this distinction in levels (more) explicit and in this
process makes the performer and -ideally- the audience aware that it's there
and *how* it works. This is unlike operations in more traditional DAW's as
there it's rarely clear if the chosen operation is exactly what's intended
or whether the composer/performer makes do with what's at hand.

One thing I have been wondering about this in this context is how
muscle-memory works both in favour and against us. It's harder to learn
highly unusual piano pieces and, worse yet, a playful shove towards a
trained martial artist could conceivably trigger his muscle memory and
result in a painfull unintended elbow to your face. I wonder how Livecoding
relates to this side of the "higher level" of instructions.

This may seem off topic in a debate on language but I'm not sure it is. I
think language too has the equivalent of involuntary "knee jerk" responses,
particularly where taboo subjects are involved ("the pil", and worse yet;
"doing it", talk about careless function overloading!).


To me this is a very exciting debate so I'm hitting "send" on this but I
have a sneaking suspision this mail will be seen as wildly off-topic by
many, then again, by now the same likely holds true for many mails to this
topic...

yours,
Kas.

------=_Part_47719_26635118.1199883371061
Content-Type: text/html; charset=ISO-8859-1
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 7bit
Content-Disposition: inline

