Date: Thu, 10 Jan 2008 01:30:57 +0100
From: douglas edric stanley <destanley
Subject: Re: [livecode] non-linguistic programming


>I would go so far as to say that ANY musical instrument is a kind of
>computer, and leave the statement open to debate.

They have some very fundamental similarities.

>2. ((Interaction))
>
>This notorious word has gained a lot of currency in the past few decades,
>but to me it's usage remains somewhat bogus.

Most people have actually dropped the term. My=20
lab, for example, has just dropped the term in=20
its name (cf. signature below, haven't had the=20
time to change it btw).

About a year back or so we all agreed that it was=20
a useless term, and this coming from people that=20
had written important papers, research, and=20
publications, and even (in my case) gotten a=20
degree based on that word.

>  For me interaction is basically
>Newton's Third Law, which guarantees that every time you hit your head
>upon a wall, you will feel a lot of hurt.

Well, actually if you go back to cybernetics,=20
interactivity is a far richer word and totally=20
redefines the activity and the subject.=20
Unfortunately though, and this has become so=20
true, it is now understood as a sort of very=20
subjective wishful thinking, and so for many=20
people just smoke and mirrors.

>  Now over time you may feel that hitting
>a wall with your head may not be such a wise=20
>thing to do, and then what remains
>in adulthood is the subconscious definition of=20
>wall - 'not to be struck with head'.
>I think the physics of our world is interactive at every level,

Well, again, interactivity was about something=20
far more specific that interacting with things,=20
people, space, etc. But we need to loose the word=20
totally, before we can go back to. Again, I'd=20
suggest that we go back to it via cybernetics=20
then see how we can get past that whole paradigm.

>  and therefore
>to say that interaction is a result of=20
>automative sensor-response computations is
>not very wise.

Yeah, again, I'd have a gazillion things to say=20
on that one, but we'll leave that for another=20
debate.

>3. ((language/linguistic))
>
>Surely the title of this thread should have been "non-textual programming",
>since even visual flowcharts or coding systems are languages in the formal
>sense?

Hmmm...
