Date: Fri, 11 Jan 2008 07:37:19 +0100
From: douglas edric stanley <destanley
Subject: Re: [livecode] non-linguistic programming


>Which made me cringe the moment
>i said it, but anyway, what I meant was - art is always a
>representation.

There are representations in art, but art is not=20
always a representation. Absolutely not.=20
Similarly, there are representations inside=20
computing, for example how you construct your=20
data model, or how you arrange your inputs. But=20
there are very real effects taking place inside=20
of computers, I hope we can all agree on that=20
one. For example, there are very real political=20
struggles taking place via computing: power,=20
social relations, money exchange, expressions of=20
all sorts, etc. And there any many other=20
phenomena taking place inside of computers:=20
calculation, simulation, recursion, etc.

Even the tree in your example has=20
representational aspects. So be careful not to=20
conflate "art" with "representation".

I make a point of this, because for me Livecoding=20
-- and even more so the TopLap manifesto -- is=20
very much a humorous redux of some of the debates=20
that have traversed the history of art, but which=20
really came into focus in the multitude of=20
activities surrounding the period of conceptual=20
art, and art after the 60's. A lot of that debate=20
surrounded the question of art and=20
representation, the repsentability of art, etc,=20
and was a playful reworking of the more formalist=20
aspects of minimalism, american abstractionism,=20
etc.

Part of the "point" of livecoding, if there is=20
one, is to precisely play with these ambiguities=20
oscillating within the representation of code,=20
the action of code, the lingustics of code, and=20
the performance of code, etc.

>Similarly, computer systems are representations of something. You can
>make a computer to represent interactivity. You might say it isn't
>'true' interactivity, but it still MEANS true interactivity. Circles
>that we draw with computers aren't 'true' circles, but we do call them
>circles.
>
>[1]: http://www.natuurkunstdrenthe.nl/index_en.php?id=3Den/home


-- 
