Date: Fri, 11 Jan 2008 16:49:39 +0100
From: Julian Rohrhuber <rohrhuber
Subject: Re: [livecode] non-linguistic programming


>
>What isn't a cultural artefact, then? Sanskrit is actually just an example
>I gave, could have been Aramaic. It is almost never spoken outside of
>temples (by priests who don't understand it) in India and some 
>Chinese universities
>where they teach and study it.
>
>
>Cultural artefaction is a cultural artefact.

http://www.iias.nl/index.php?q=node/368


// some catuscoti variations
(
a = ["either % or %", "both % and %", "neither % nor %"];
x = { |i, x=("true"), y=("false")| format(a[i], x, y) };
f = { #[0, 1, 2].scramble.keep(2) };
g = { |i=0, n=1, s1, s2|
	var k, l;
	#k, l = f.value;
	if(n>1) {
		x.(
			i,
			g.(k, n-1, s1, s2),
			g.(l, n-1, s1, s2)
		)

	} {
		x.(i, s1, s2)
	}
};



z = {|n=1, s1, s2|
	var r = g.([0, 1, 2].choose, n, s1, s2);
	r[0] = r[0].toUpper;
	quote(r ++ ".")
}
);

z.(1)
z.(2)
z.(4)

"Both neither true nor false and both true and false."


"Either both either either true or false or neither true nor false 
and both either true or false and neither true nor false or neither 
either neither true nor false or both true and false nor both neither 
true nor false and either true or false."
-- 





.


Date: Sat, 12 Jan 2008 08:15:42 +0530
From: AlgoMantra <algomantra
Subject: Re: [livecode] non-linguistic programming


