Date: Fri, 22 Feb 2008 16:18:17 +0000
From: Nick Collins <nc272
Subject: Re: [livecode] code taunts


Hi Marcel,

your work is very interesting and I wish I could attend one of your public=20
battles! Thanks for sharing the paper. Just to clarify, this isn't my=20
recollection of the Barcelona contest:

 their disapproval of Collins=E2=80=99 loading of
pre-programmed code fragments with boos and hisses

I spent the first ten minutes just coding a complex microtonal system based =

on the Babylonian square root algorithm. I then explored this with sound=20
from around 10-15 minutes in; but all was from scratch.

after 15 mins, when Ge had dropped out to recompile ChucK, I had to switch=20
to working with some other stuff just to cover (in retrospect I should have =

worked further on the Babylonian material, but panicked); but I did so=20
within my live coding environment, and was live coding throughout, though=20
less from scratch and more by modification.

It was Ge who ran preprogrammed presets in the first half of the=20
competition. However, neither of us had anticipated the public competition=20
aspect would be so dominant, and our preparations were very different to=20
what turned out to be required. I make my full confession in the 2007 NIME=20
paper. I typed what I should have typed had I prepared for battle, in my=20
movie posted the other day.

I was the most disappointed by that gig of any I've been involved with, but =

a great learning experience under real-time constraints! I had been=20
practising for weeks before, but not the right material, and had to adapt=20
to the setting in a way that I wasn't prepared for. Note that I make no=20
defence of the quality of that 2005 concert.

best
Nick












