Date: Wed, 5 Mar 2008 16:14:23 -0000 (GMT)
Subject: Re: [livecode] lew
From: "Dave Griffiths" <dave


This reminds me a lot of the intention of the arc langauge, which I've
been meaning to mention here for a while: http://arclanguage.org/

Paul Graham is a controversial figure, but some of his thoughts are
interesting when looked at with a livecoding hat on.

>
> Interesting manifesto for a language designed for experimentation:
>   http://www.4p8.com/lew/manifesto.html
>
>
>
>




Date: Wed, 5 Mar 2008 17:45:01 -0000 (GMT)
Subject: Re: [livecode] lew
From: "Dave Griffiths" <dave



>
> Interesting manifesto for a language designed for experimentation:
>   http://www.4p8.com/lew/manifesto.html

The screenshots look really nice too actually, although I'd cheekily clai=
m
I could write similar things with less code in fluxus - but this brings u=
p
an interesting point that arc has triggered too, is shorter code
neccisarily clearer?

At what point does it become unintelligible? It's a bit like an 'uncanny
valley' class of problem.

Programming fashion seems to be lurching back in the direction of less
text, probably because most programmers deal with C++ and Java, where
there are lots of VeryVerboseNamesForEverything :)

cheers,

dave



