Date: Thu, 06 Mar 2008 07:46:48 -0500
From: Charles Turner <vze26m98
Subject: Re: [livecode] syntax free


On Thu, 06 Mar 2008 11:56:20 +0000 (GMT), Dave Griffiths wrote:
> I think that the beauty of visual programming languages are that the
> contraints are obvious in that they are visible.

Not necessarily a a response to the spirit of the conversation here, 
but Max/MSP and Pure Data enforce a hierarchy of inlets, where the 
"action" of an object doesn't occur until something arrives at the 
leftmost outlet. Also, evaluation occurs on screen from left to right, 
so program behavior can change depending on the location of an object 
with respect to others. (This last bit is from memory, so I could be 
wholly or partially wrong. I think also PD has an even weirder scheme.)

Some might find this approach/visualization of Forth to be suggestive 
of Max and PD:

<http://www.forth.org/forth_intro/stackflo.htm>

Best, Charles



Date: Thu, 6 Mar 2008 13:54:37 +0100
From: Kassen <signal.automatique
Subject: Re: [livecode] syntax free


------=_Part_19159_26994339.1204808077883
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=ISO-8859-1
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 7bit
Content-Disposition: inline

On 06/03/2008, alex <alex@hiddenorg> wrote:
>
>
> I think I was misunderstood here.  I wasn't saying that max/puredata
> don't have syntax, but the opposite.  I was saying that they _do_ have
> syntax, but asking how could we replace that syntax of wires with a
> semantics of space?


Very good. I'm happy we got that out of the way.



> Or one on a non-euclidean surface, perhaps where you could zoom in
> infinitely.



I think this "surface" if going to have to be non-euclidean in rather a lot
of dimensions. It looks to me like we will be "overloading space" rather
heavily. MAX already overloads the meaning of space; space is used as the
equivalent of comments in that a spacial ordering is (typically) used to
indicate the structure of the patch yet MAX also uses the left to right
ordering of modules to determine execution order. Those two may not line up.

One thing that bothers me in spatial ordering (and sorting records....) is
that if we have two points A and B that are close to each other and in some
sort of relationship and place a third point C so it's near to A it will
also be near to B... which may not be intended.

We can accept that (like we accept changing pitch or volume will also change
timbre in many instruments) or we can involve a extra dimension (say colour
or height or direction) or have a gesture that "curves space".

This is one aspect where I think the Reactable deals with the topic in a way
that's still a bit naive (though solving this will likely go at the expense
of intuitivity)


Yours,
Kas.

