From: nescivi <nescivi
Subject: [livecode] looking for a cooperation partner in India
Date: Fri, 07 Mar 2008 14:53:04 -0500


Hi,

I posted this on the sc-users list and on the linux audio list before, but it 
occurred to me, that I might actually have some luck on this list...


As part of a dance-interaction piece we are developing with a dance company in 
Bangalore, we are looking for someone who lives in India and who is 
interested in this kind of thing and possibly, if it all works out, tour with 
the company.

I will be in charge of developing the code, converting the interaction 
concepts into working code for the performance, so we are looking for someone 
who is willing to delve into SuperCollider [1] enough so that (s)he will be 
able to set up the system for the show, and run code during the show, and 
troubleshoot if necessary.
Development of the piece will be over the whole of this year, and then in the 
next years the piece will (hopefully) tour.

Any other experience with software (like max, pd, processing, etc) or hardware 
(electronics, sensor interfaces, wireless systems) comes in handy too.

We don't expect to find the SuperCollider-expert right away (though that would 
be great if we did), so if you are just starting with SuperCollider that's 
fine, you will learn along the way.

Please contact me off-list if you are interested and happen to live in India, 
to get details. If you think you might know someone or have good ideas for 
how to find someone, that would also be great.

sincerely,
Marije

[1] because of the technology involved, linux or mac based


Subject: Re: [livecode] syntax free
From: alex <alex
Date: Sat, 08 Mar 2008 22:31:24 +0000


On Fri, 2008-03-07 at 16:13 +0000, evan.raskob [lists] wrote:
> alex, can you please explain this point further?  i feel like you've =20
> got some specific definitions of "syntax" and "language" in your head =20
> which i might like to have in mine as well.

By 'language' I mean human-computer interface, in particular a textual
(symbolic) one.  By "syntax" I mean the grammar of such a language, the
rules of play as separate from the meaning or semantics.

As I understand it, in his book "conceptual spaces" G=C3=A4rdenfors sees
meaning (semantics) being represented not within syntax but within a
geometric 'conceptual' space. =20

I can't really answer better than that, I don't have a grounding in
linguistics so can't really look on this stuff critically, and need to
read more before I understand it properly.  But I do like the idea of
meaning in terms of shape, for example the idea that metaphor is the
application of a shape from one domain to another.

alex




Date: Sun, 9 Mar 2008 07:20:26 +0530
From: AlgoMantra <algomantra
