<div>It's an interesting point, and certainly worth looking into. =A0I =
think this touches on the language of performance, a subject which has a =
long and interesting history (but which I am definitely not qualified to =
discuss at length). =A0 For example, I enjoy operas, but have no idea =
what people are saying most of the time. =A0Same for French hip hop, or =
Russian alt-rock, but that doesn't mean I can't appreciate it. =A0The =
language you code in is important, whether its FLOSS or not is a side =
point. =A0 For example, It'd be interesting to see someone livecoding in =
a non-Western language like Mandarin, and possibly not much different =
than watching them code in a proprietary programming language that I had =
no access to. =A0Personally, I wouldn't mix FLOSS with livecoding =
discussions, because they feel like completely different subjects. =
=A0Would you discuss with Picasso how much he paid for his brush? =A0Or =
Da Vinci? =A0Doubtful, because its besides the point of their work. =A0 =
=46rom an anthropological or documentary or personal standpoint, =
however, I can understand, but I always wind up livecoding in =
MaxMSPJitter and it certainly didn't cost me $10K and it's widely =
available, so why not?</div><div><br></div><div>Alex: the concept of =
"sourcecode feedback" is fascinating... the computer commenting in the =
course code itself, as a conversation with the user? =A0tantalizing. =A0i =
can imagine the day when my Processing app adds itself as the author of =
a function in the javadoc, and leaves the comment "you really fucked =
this up, so i'm taking over; love, the =
