From: Marcel Wierckx <Marcel
Subject: Re: [livecode] live coding and free software - feedback rqrd
Date: Wed, 2 Apr 2008 17:33:54 +0200


Hi Alex

Very informative article with some very good points. I do have some =20
observations however.

you write:
"No wonder then that we hear anecdotes of audience members feeling =20
alienated by laptop
performances where screens are hidden. They could close their eyes, =20
but couldn=92t they then have
stayed at home, listening to a recording?"

how is this different from going to an orchestra performance? I could =20=

also close my eyes and pretend I'm listening to a cd. The difference =20
has nothing to do with the laptop, but everything to do with =20
authenticity. Today, one goes to a live performance more for the =20
event than for the music. Kim Cascone has some interesting things to =20
say in that respect (see "Laptop Music =96 counterfeiting aura in the =20=

age of infinite reproduction", or "Grain, Sequence, System: Three =20
Levels of Reception in the Performance of Laptop Music"). An =20
orchestra performance is authentic because it is impossible that it's =20=

not. That cannot be said of a laptop performance.

you write:
"The practice of programming is informed by the corporate world of =20
business software, with its talk
of formal design, unit testing and ISO quality assurance. This all =20
attempts to drive the creativity
out of programming so that software may be as predictable as possible."

I find this to be an unnecessarily pessimistic statement. Only a tiny =20=

fraction of my students go on to write commercial software. The vast =20
majority write software to build musical instruments, create artistic =20=

installations, perform live electronic music, work with theater =20
performers, dancers, musicians, etc. etc. The 'corporate world' might =20=

inform computer science faculties of some universities, but in art =20
institutions where the craft of writing software is taught as a means =20=

of creative expression I personally don't see any significant =20
influence. Furthermore I think it would be difficult to prove that =20
the 'corporate world' is attempting to "drive the creativity out of =20
programming". =46rom what I know about Google I might infer that the =20
opposite happens.

In general, your article touches on a theme which is very important =20
to me - the use of technology as a means for personal, =20
individualistic expression. However any technology which has =20
developed beyond the limits of what is immediately understandable to =20
an individual brings with it problems of what can be considered =20
individualistic expression. To use the Picasso analogy: I could watch =20=

him smear paint across a canvas and immediately afterwards run out to =20=

the forest, find a branch, pluck some hair off the back of a squirrel =20=

to make a brush, and perhaps use my own blood to make a painting. Not =20=

so when seeing a live coder: I would be dependent upon the =20
generations of designers which put their intellects to the task of =20
developing a machine which I might never in my lifetime fully =20
understand. Because after all, living coding is ultimately the =20
control of a machine which is the product of another human's =20
creativity. I don't say this as a criticism of technology-driven art, =20=

but as an observation, and I am constantly asking myself how I should =20=

feel about its implications. As you quote Cage saying: "We=92re getting =20=

music made by man himself: not just one man." What then can I create =20
which I can truly call my own?

Thanks for sharing your article.

Marcel


