<DIV><FONT face=3DArial size=3D2>Hi There</FONT></DIV>
<DIV><FONT face=3DArial size=3D2></FONT>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV><FONT face=3DArial size=3D2>Well yes the underlying thing is to =
pass sequences=20
of numbers to the operating system thence they get passed to the sound =
card=20
driver and finally accross the system bus to the sound card/sound =
chipset which=20
converts the numbers into voltages. Programs which make sound generate =
this=20
stream of samples themselves using various algorithms and pass them to =
the OS.=20
</FONT></DIV>
<DIV><FONT face=3DArial size=3D2></FONT>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV><FONT face=3DArial size=3D2>Operating systems provide various =
interfaces (API)=20
to pass buffers of samples between the userspace program and&nbsp; the =
soundcard=20
driver -- on Linux this is usually ALSA or OSS. JACK sits on top of =
these. It's=20
more or less the same situation on other platforms. For cross platform =
work=20
there are libraries which wrap multiple APIs with the same programming =
interface=20
such as rtAudio or PortAudio (<A=20
href=3D"http://www.portaudio.com">www.portaudio.com</A>)...</FONT></DIV>
<DIV><FONT face=3DArial size=3D2></FONT>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV><FONT face=3DArial size=3D2>HTH</FONT></DIV>
<DIV><FONT face=3DArial size=3D2></FONT>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV><FONT face=3DArial size=3D2>Ross.</FONT></DIV>
<DIV><FONT face=3DArial size=3D2></FONT>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV><FONT face=3DArial size=3D2></FONT>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV><FONT face=3DArial size=3D2></FONT>&nbsp;</DIV>
