Date: Sat, 03 May 2008 08:49:24 -0400
From: Charles Turner <vze26m98
Subject: [livecode] Oops! Re:  audio source in linux


Sorry, a little early for me this morning. The Chua example, although=20
not uninteresting, wrote to a file, not to the audio system. Here's the=20
iForth include for basic sound support and playing WAV files:

(*
 * LANGUAGE    : ANS Forth with DFW extensions
 * PROJECT     : Forth Environments
 * DESCRIPTION : Play .WAV files in the background
 * CATEGORY    : Sound Utilities
 * AUTHOR      : Marcel Hendrix
 * LAST CHANGE : Sunday, March 30, 2008, 1:04 AM, Marcel Hendrix, fixed=20
race condition
 * LAST CHANGE : March 2008, Hanno Schwalm, using the old 151 SYSCALL=20
parameters again and
                 trying to find files in a better way
 * LAST CHANGE : May 24, 2003, Marcel Hendrix, new call 151 (also=20
reading)
 * LAST CHANGE : November 7, 1996, Marcel Hendrix, added 'new' Win95=20
.WAV format
 * LAST CHANGE : February 2, 1996, Marcel Hendrix, added .SND .AU=20
support
 * LAST CHANGE : January 20, 1996, Marcel Hendrix, Linux version
 * LAST CHANGE : July 18, 1995, Marcel Hendrix, DPMI update
 * LAST CHANGE : July 2, 1995, Marcel Hendrix, DPMI changes
 * LAST CHANGE : February 13, 1995, Marcel Hendrix
 *)



        NEEDS -miscutil

        REVISION -pwavlinu "=C4=C4=C4 Play .WAV files     Version 1.08 =C4=
=C4=C4"

=09PRIVATES


DOC The interface to the sound devices under Linux.
(*
 This code assumes you have a Linux kernel with sound support.=20
Specifically,
 /dev/mixer and /dev/dsp are supposed to be available.
*)
ENDDOC


: SET-SAMPLE-RATE ( n -- )
=091 #146 SYSCALL DROP ABORT" Can't set sample-rate" ;

: SET-#CHANNELS ( n -- )
=091 #147 SYSCALL DROP ABORT" Can't set the requested channel=20
configuration" ;

: SET-#BITS ( n -- )
=091 #148 SYSCALL DROP ABORT" Can't set the requested number of bits per=20
sample" ;

: SET-PCM-VOLUME ( l r -- ) =09=09\ in percent
=09#100 MIN ><  SWAP #100 MIN  OR
=094 2 #150 SYSCALL DROP ABORT" couldn't set PCM volume" ;

: SET-MAIN-VOLUME ( l r -- )=09=09\ in percent
=09#100 MIN ><  SWAP #100 MIN  OR
=090 2 #150 SYSCALL DROP ABORT" couldn't set MAIN volume" ;

: BUFFER-SPACE? ( -- bytes_free )
=090 #152 SYSCALL ABORT" problem getting audio buffer space" ;

: RESET-SOUND ( -- )
=090 #153 SYSCALL DROP ABORT" Can't reset sound device" ;

-- This has undesired side effects as the driver does not seem to know=20
how many bytes are 'waiting'.
: FLUSH-SOUND ( -- )
=090 #154 SYSCALL DROP ABORT" Can't flush sound device" ;

: >SOUNDBUFFER ( addr u -- )
=09DUP 0=3D IF  2DROP EXIT  ENDIF
=092 #151 SYSCALL
=09?DUP IF PAD #256 ROT ERROR>TEXT DROP TYPE ENDIF
=09DROP ;


DOC
(*
    /*\
    |*|----=3D=3D=3D=3D< ".WAV" file format >=3D=3D=3D=3D----
    |*|
 0  |*|     4 bytes 'RIFF'
 1  |*|     4 bytes <length1>=09    ; length_file-8 (length of what=20
follows)
 2  |*|     4 bytes 'WAVE'
 3  |*|     4 bytes 'fmt '=09    ; block =3D name:4, size:4, bytes:size
 4  |*|     4 bytes <length2>=09    ; length of 'fmt' block
 5  |*|     2 bytes  01 =09    ; format tag
    |*|     2 bytes  xx =09    ; channels (1=3Dmono, 2=3Dstereo)
 6  |*|     4 bytes  xxxx=09    ; samples per second
 7  |*|     4 bytes  xxxx=09    ; average samples per second
 8  |*|     2 bytes  01 =09    ; block alignment (shown for mono 8-bit)
    |*|     2 bytes  08 =09    ; bits per sample (shown for 8-bit)
    |*|     ? bytes=09=09    ; fill to length2 bytes
    |*|     4 bytes 'data'
   .....    <more blocks>=09    ; their name is not 'data'
    |*|     4 bytes ?=09=09    ; sometimes: actual sample data byte count,=
=20
else 'ja  '
    |*|       bytes <sample data>
    |*|
    |*| =09Note: the sample data must end on an even byte boundary.
    |*| =09      All numeric data fields are in the Intel format
    |*| =09      of low-high byte ordering.
    |*|
    \*/
*)
ENDDOC


    2 =3D: stereo
    1 =3D: mono
    8 =3D: 8bits
  #16 =3D: 16bits

-- Allow the caller to define pitching (HACK!)

[UNDEFINED] pitching [IF]  1 1  DVALUE pitching=09\ pitch up or down=20
(control sample rate)
=09   =09   [THEN]

FALSE  VALUE ForceStereo?=09=09=09\ overrule a file's stereo/mono indicator

-- Because the Linux DMA buffers are LARGE, sending a single block is=20
enough.
-- However, this has the disadvantage that sound effects can not
-- be aborted (e.g MIDI): they're so short that they fit in a single=20
buffer.
-- In this case, do not send buffer-space? bytes, but just enough bytes=20
to
-- bridge the gap to the next MORE-BLOCK? call. For instance, a 44.1=20
kHz stereo
-- sample needs 17.64 Kbytes to play for 100 ms.

: ONLY-BLOCK ( c-addr u -- )=09=09\ Does it in one go.
=09>SOUNDBUFFER =09=09 =09\ Linux driver is synchronous
=09RESET-SOUND =09=09=09\ ???? first flush then reset is even worse
=09FLUSH-SOUND ;

: BLOCKS->DMA ( -- ) ;=09=09=09\ send (a)nother block(s)

-- Under Linux, the parameters are set without closing/opening the=20
device.
: sparameters! ( samplerate #channels 8/16? -- )
=09RESET-SOUND ( make sure the device breaks current sound, takes the new=
=20
parameters )
=09SET-#BITS
=09ForceStereo? IF DROP stereo ENDIF SET-#CHANNELS
=09pitching */ SET-SAMPLE-RATE ;


CREATE h1  PRIVATE   TEXT% RIFFWAVEfmt data%
CREATE wavheader #1024 CHARS ALLOT PRIVATE

: SET-WAVINFO ( addr -- ) wavheader #1024 MOVE ;

-- Tests for 'WAVExxxxRIFFfmt '
: WAVE?=09( -- bool )
=09wavheader @ h1 @ =3D
=09wavheader 2 CELL[] 2@  h1 CELL+ 2@ D=3D  AND ; PRIVATE

: wav-params ( addr -- 'wav /wav )
=095 LOCALS| #recs 'head |
=09'head 4 CELL[] =09\ length2
=09BEGIN
=09  @+ + ( name, count, bytes)
=09  -1 +TO #recs #recs 0=3D ABORT" unstructured .WAV file"
=09  @+  h1 3 CELL[] @ =3D ( 'data')
=09UNTIL
=09@+ >S
=09DUP 'head 2 CELLS + -  'head CELL+ @  SWAP -
=09S> UMIN ;

: .WHAT ( -- )
=09CR WAVE? 0=3D ABORT" Not a simple .WAV file."
=09." Samplerate is " wavheader 6 CELL[] ? ." Herz, "
=09wavheader 7 CELL[] ? ." bytes/sec (average)." CR
=09wavheader 5 CELL[] 2+ C@=20
=09CASE=20
=09  1 OF ." Mono, "   ENDOF
=09  2 OF ." Stereo, " ENDOF=20
=09       DUP 0 .R ." -channel, "=20
=09ENDCASE
=09wavheader 8 CELL[] 2+ C@hidden" bits per sample, "
=09wavheader wav-params NIP DEC. ." bytes. "
=09CR ." Speedup is " #100 pitching */ #100 - 0 .R ." %, ForceStereo? is "
=09ForceStereo? IF ." ON" ELSE ." OFF" ENDIF '.' EMIT ;


-- Shortcut: must fit completely into memory! (This is unix, right...)
: .WAV ( c-addr u -- )
=090 0 LOCALS| infile storage |
=09R/O BIN OPEN-FILE ?FILE TO infile
=09infile FILE-SIZE ?FILE DROP
=09DUP ALLOCATE ?ALLOCATE TO storage
=09storage SWAP infile READ-FILE ?FILE DROP
=09infile CLOSE-FILE ?FILE
=09storage SET-WAVINFO ( for .what)
=09WAVE? 0=3D IF ." This is not a .wav file." storage FREE ?ALLOCATE EXIT=
=20
ENDIF
=09storage 6 CELL[] @ =09=09=09\ samplerate
=09storage 5 CELL[] 2+ C@ =09=09 =09\ quad/stereo/mono?
=09storage 8 CELL[] 2+ C@ sparameters! =09\ bits/sample
=09storage wav-params ONLY-BLOCK=09
=09FLUSH-SOUND=09=09=09=09\ wait till everything is transferred to the driv=
er
=09storage FREE ?ALLOCATE ;

: .WAVSPEC ( c-addr u -- )
=09R/O BIN OPEN-FILE ?FILE 0 0 LOCALS| /buf 'buf ihndl |
=09ihndl FILE-SIZE ?FILE DROP TO /buf
=09/buf ALLOCATE ?ALLOCATE TO 'buf
=09'buf /buf ihndl READ-FILE ?FILE TO /buf
=09'buf SET-WAVINFO
=09'buf FREE ?ALLOCATE
=09ihndl CLOSE-FILE ?FILE=20
=09.WHAT ;

-- Easy way to play a MIDI file; doesn't work for Linux
: .MID ( c-addr u -- )
=092 #159 SYSCALL DROP ABORT" midi player error" ;

-- Play any file when the parameters are known.
: .SOUND ( samplerate #channels 8/16 c-addr u -- )
=09R/O BIN OPEN-FILE ?FILE 0 0 LOCALS| /buf 'buf ihndl |
=09sparameters!
=09ihndl FILE-SIZE ?FILE DROP TO /buf
=09/buf ALLOCATE ?ALLOCATE TO 'buf
=09'buf /buf ihndl READ-FILE ?FILE TO /buf
=09'buf SET-WAVINFO
=09'buf wav-params ONLY-BLOCK=20
=09ihndl CLOSE-FILE ?FILE=20
=09FLUSH-SOUND=09\ wait till everything is transferred to the driver
=09'buf FREE ?ALLOCATE ;


-- The idea is to execute a son of SNIPPET to play the first soundbyte=20
block.
-- After that, execute MORE-BLOCKS? frequently, in order to output the=20
other
-- blocks. Calling MORE-BLOCKS? is typically done when the foreground=20
program
-- has nothing better to do.

-- It's not an error to start a new sample before the previous one has=20
finished.
CREATE buff PRIVATE  #256 CHARS ALLOT
: SNIPPET ( c-addr u -- )
=09CREATE=090 0 LOCALS| infile storage |
=09=09S" IFORTH" SEARCH-ENV$ IF buff PACK DROP S" /" buff PLACE+ ELSE 0=20
buff ! THEN
=09=09buff PLACE+  buff COUNT  R/O BIN OPEN-FILE ?FILE TO infile
=09=09infile FILE-SIZE ?FILE DROP
=09=09DUP ALLOCATE ?ALLOCATE TO storage
=09=09storage ,
=09=09storage SWAP infile READ-FILE ?FILE DROP
=09=09infile CLOSE-FILE ?FILE
=09=09storage wav-params , ,
=09FORGET>=09@ FREE ?ALLOCATE
=09DOES> =09@+ SWAP @+ SWAP @ LOCALS| 'wav /wav 'head |
=09=09'head 6 CELL[] @ ( samplerate )
=09=09'head 5 CELL[] 2+ C@ ( #channels )
=09=09'head 8 CELL[] 2+ C@ ( bits/sample)  sparameters!
=09=09'wav /wav >SOUNDBUFFER ( does NOT flush ) ;

-- example: WHATSIT BOING
: .WHATSIT ( "name" -- )
=09' >BODY @  wavheader #1024 CMOVE  .WHAT ;

:ABOUT=09CR ." This code only works when sound support is available."
=09CR .~ Reconfigure / recompile the kernel when needed ("insmod sound").~
=09CR
=09CR .~ Try: S" /PerfectRoot/windows/media/ding.wav" .WAV~
=09CR .~ Try: S" /PerfectRoot/windows/media/onestop.mid" .MID~
=09CR .~ Or:  44100 stereo 8bits S" /PerfectRoot/windows/media/ding.wav"=20
.SOUND~
=09CR ." After a file has run .WHAT shows parameters."
=09CR ." 98 100 TO pitching        -- play back at 98% original speed"
=09CR ." TRUE TO ForceStereo?      -- always playback as stereo"
=09CR ." stereo | mono             -- set stereo / mono (only for .SOUND)"
=09CR ." 8bits  | 16bits           -- set sample size   (only for .SOUND)"
=09CR ." wav-params ( a1 -- a2 u ) -- get buffer address and size from=20
header"
=09CR ." Note: a mono file is up one octave when played in stereo."
=09CR
=09CR ." <fname> SNIPPET <name>    -- build  name  to do <fname> .WAV"
=09CR ." MORE-BLOCKS?              -- ( -- TRUE=3Dmore ) outputs as many=20
samples as possible."=20
=09CR ." ONLY-BLOCK                -- ( 'wav size -- ) outputs as many=20
samples as possible."=20
=09CR ." BLOCKS->DMA               -- outputs as many samples as=20
possible." ;


=09#75 #75 SET-PCM-VOLUME
=09#75 #75 SET-MAIN-VOLUME


=09NESTING @ 2 <=3D [IF] .ABOUT -pwavlinu CR [THEN]

=09DEPRIVE

NESTING @ 2 <=3D
  [IF]
1 =3D: snds
=09CR .( ** The samples needed may not be present. Please edit **)

snds [IF]
=09S" examples/orkest/wavs/boing.wav"  =09SNIPPET boing
=09S" examples/orkest/wavs/aah.wav"=09SNIPPET aah
=09S" examples/orkest/wavs/shotgn31.wav"  =09SNIPPET shot
=09S" examples/orkest/wavs/owl.wav"  =09SNIPPET one
=09S" examples/orkest/wavs/boathorn.wav"=09SNIPPET bugle
   [ELSE]
=09S" examples/orkest/wavs/bassdrum.wav"=09SNIPPET bassdrum
=09S" examples/orkest/wavs/cowbell.wav"=09SNIPPET cowbell
=09S" examples/orkest/wavs/hihatb.wav"=09SNIPPET hihatb
=09S" examples/orkest/wavs/hihat.wav"=09SNIPPET hihat
=09S" examples/orkest/wavs/handclap.wav"=09SNIPPET handclap
=09S" examples/orkest/wavs/cymbal.wav"=09SNIPPET cymbal
=09S" examples/orkest/wavs/hightom.wav"=09SNIPPET hightom
=09S" examples/orkest/wavs/lowtom.wav"=09SNIPPET lowtom
=09S" examples/orkest/wavs/midtom.wav"=09SNIPPET midtom
=09S" examples/orkest/wavs/maracass.wav"=09SNIPPET maracass
=09S" examples/orkest/wavs/hibongo.wav"=09SNIPPET highbongo
=09S" examples/orkest/wavs/lowbongo.wav"=09SNIPPET lowbongo
=09S" examples/orkest/wavs/cardbox.wav"=09SNIPPET cardbox
=09S" examples/orkest/wavs/woodblk.wav"=09SNIPPET woodblock
   [THEN]

#50 VALUE delay

: sound ( -- )
=09BLOCKS->DMA
=09delay MS  #150 CHOOSE #50 + #100  TO pitching ;

: TEST=09BEGIN
[ snds ]=20
  [IF]
=09boing sound
=09aah   sound
=09shot  sound
=09one   sound
[ELSE]
=09bassdrum  sound
=09cowbell=09  sound
=09hihatb    sound
=09cymbal    sound
=09hihat =09  sound
=09cardbox=09  sound
=09handclap  sound
=09hightom   sound
=09midtom    sound
=09lowtom=09  sound
=09maracass  sound
=09lowbongo  sound
=09highbongo sound
=09woodblock sound
[THEN]
=09#50 CHOOSE #50 + #100  TO pitching
=09KEY?
=09UNTIL
=09KEY DROP ;

: TEST2=09BEGIN
[ snds ]=20
  [IF]
=09one=09  sound
[ELSE]
=09bassdrum  sound
=09cowbell=09  sound
=09hihatb    sound
=09cymbal    sound
=09hihat =09  sound
=09cardbox=09  sound
=09handclap  sound
=09hightom   sound
=09midtom    sound
=09lowtom=09  sound
=09maracass  sound
=09lowbongo  sound
=09highbongo sound
=09woodblock sound
[THEN]
=09pitching >S  5 + #100 MOD #50 MAX S>  TO pitching
=09KEY?
=09UNTIL
=09KEY DROP ;

[THEN]
                              (* End of Source *)


Date: Sat, 3 May 2008 16:21:23 +0200
From: Julian Rohrhuber <rohrhuber
Subject: Re: [livecode] audio source in linux


>I can see the concept of minimising the middle-man in software but 
>on the level of what you will actually write not much need to be 
>different.  CK an SC (PD is obviously a bit different being 
>graphical) are perfectly fine with with sending the outcome of a 
>equation straight to the output. You lose the nice ready-made Ugens 
>and their optimisation but you can. I imagine that at that point 
>shell-scripting and ChucK would start to look a lot alike as math is 
>math.
>
>
>Hm, makes sense. I'm more interested at this point in understanding 
>the mathematics of sound, rather than creating any musical variety 
>of it...

There are many branches of mathematics. Sound synthesis languages are 
a mathematics of sound, which have to take into account that the 
being of sound is more than its waveform. Just as any mathematics, it 
is not trivial to describe something formally. 'Low level' system 
commands may well turn out to be less mathematical than 'high level' 
programming languages. Despite this, it is a nice project! If you 
want to be close to discourses such as those of mathematical logic 
though, Haskell may be a good alternative.
-- 





.


