From: Andrew Brown <a.brown
Date: Wed, 6 Aug 2008 10:26:11 +1000
Subject: [livecode] Australian PhD scholarship


Dear Toplap folk,

This scholarship opportunity may be of interest to people on this list, and
I encourage further distribution to those you think may be interested.

Cheers,

Andrew
-----------

PhD Scholarship in Adaptive Media

The Australasian CRC for Interaction Design (ACID) is offering a new
doctoral scholarship for a suitably qualified candidate to undertake
research into computational processes for generative music and graphics.
This scholarship is funded by ACID for a period of three years. The positio=
n
will be based in the Creative Industries Faculty at the Queensland
University of Technology (QUT) in Brisbane, Australia.

ACID is a leader in the research and design of innovative technologies and
digital media that support new forms of interaction and collaboration.

The successful applicant will work with a team of researchers working on
ACID's Adaptive Media project. This project investigates new methods for
providing computational support for creative activities through generative
algorithmic processes that extend or automate creation of digital media
content.

The successful applicant will suggest a doctoral study that strongly aligns
with this project and will work with Associate Professor Andrew Brown and
Research Fellow Andrew Sorensen. Applicants must also successfully apply fo=
r
admission to the doctoral project at QUT.

The doctoral scholarship is valued at $20K per annum (tax exempt) and may b=
e
renewed, subject to satisfactory progress.

Applications are invited from both Australian citizens and International
Students applying to study at QUT. Successful applicants are expected to
enrol in 2008.

Further information is available from Associate Professor Andrew Brown, PO
Box 2008, Kelvin Grove, Qld, 4059 (Phone: 07 3337 7821; Fax: 07 3337 7834;
Email: andrew@hidden Applications should be sent direct to Associate
Professor Andrew Brown and should include a curriculum vitae, a copy of an
academic transcript, and the names and contact details of at least two
referees.

Closing Date: Friday, 31 August 2008



From: alex <alex
Date: Wed, 06 Aug 2008 22:01:17 +0100
Subject: [livecode] new instruction


After a summer break, instructionset is back:

[August 2008] Surprise

    According to the principle of least surprise, often cited in
    programming literature, software should be invisible. Write some
    software that only conforms to this principle for 10 seconds or so
    before astonishing the user in some manner. Code obfuscation is
    optional.
    http://instructionset.org/instruction/14/

You are also welcome to implement instructions from previous months.

Instructionset now has its own mailing list, so this will be the last
mailout to external mailing lists.  You can subscribe via the website:

    http://instructionset.org/

RSS/Atom feeds also available.

cheers



From: alex <alex
Date: Mon, 11 Aug 2008 15:09:15 +0100
Subject: [livecode] make art festival



Hi,

I'm helping put together an evening of live coding in Poitiers, France
on Saturday 29th November as part of the fine Make Art festival
(http://makeart.goto10.org/).  If you're up for doing a
talk/performance/workshop then please let me know.  

The catch is that this is a festival for artists using/making free
software, and they're being strict about the operating systems this
year, so you're not allowed to use mac os/windows/other closed OS.  Also
I'm afraid they probably only have money to bring people from around
Europe.

This will be a nice event, please get in touch if you want to be
involved.

Cheers,

alex

        



Date: Mon, 11 Aug 2008 15:57:10 +0100
