*from wikipedia:

Coltan smuggling has also been implicated as a major source of income =20=

for the military occupation of Congo. An activist website, Toward =20
Freedom, states that the search for coltan has fueled a brutal =20
conflict in the Democratic Republic of Congo; they state that demand =20
for coltan has caused Rwandan military groups and western mining =20
companies to seek hundreds of millions of dollars worth of the rare =20
metal, often by forcing prisoners-of-war and even children to work in =20=

the country's coltan mines. [9]
To many, this raises ethical questions akin to those of conflict =20
diamonds. Owing to the difficulty of distinguishing legitimate from =20
illegitimate mining operations, several electronicsmanufacturers have =20=

decided to forgo central African coltan altogether, relying on other =20
sources.[citation needed] The high-tech industry's demand for tantalum =20=

clearly has fueled an increase in coltan mining worldwide =96 including =20=

in the Congo region.
Toward Freedom states that the 2000 launch of the Sony PS2 required a =20=

large increase in production of electric capacitors, which are =20
primarily made with tantalum, which greatly increased the world price =20=

of the powder from $49/pound to a $275/pound, resulting in accelerated =20=

mining of the Congolese hills containing coltan. Sales in computers, =20
mobile phones, and DVD players spiked around this same time. Sony =20
claims it has discontinued its use of tantalum acquired from the =20
Congo, and sourced it from a variety of mines in several different =20
countries. Researcher David Barouski states =93The coltan ore trades =20
hands so many times from when it is mined to when SONY gets a =20
processed product, that a company often has no idea where the original =20=

coltan ore came from, and frankly don't care to know. But statistical =20=

analysis shows it to be nearly inconceivable that SONY made all its =20
PlayStations without using Congolese coltan." [9]
All three countries named by the United Nations as smugglers of coltan =20=

have denied being involved. Austrian journalist Klaus Werner has =20
documented links between multi-national companies like Bayer and the =20
illegal coltan traffic.[10] Likewise has Johann Hari written on the =20
connections between coltan resources and the genocide in Congo.[11]=20
[12] A United Nations committee investigating the plunder of gems and =20=

minerals in the Congo listed in its final report[7] approximately 125 =20=

companies and individuals involved in business activities breaching =20
international norms. Companies accused of irresponsible corporate =20
behavior are for example Cabot Corporation, Eagle Wings Resources =20
International,[13] George Forrest Group[14] and OM Group.[15]


